def cloud_pairs():
    """Cloud-specific: GKE Autopilot, EKS Fargate, spot sizing."""
    p = "expert-operational-knowledge"
    return [
        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-010",
            "We're running on GKE Autopilot. How does right-sizing work differently than on standard GKE?",
            "## GKE Autopilot Right-Sizing\n\nAutopilot changes the economics and mechanics of right-sizing significantly.\n\n**Key differences from standard GKE:**\n\n1. **You pay for requests, not nodes.** In standard GKE, you pay for node instances regardless of utilisation. In Autopilot, you pay per pod based on CPU and memory requests. This means:\n   - Over-provisioned requests directly increase cost (no 'free' headroom from node slack)\n   - Under-provisioned requests can cause OOM or throttling\n   - Right-sizing has DIRECT 1:1 cost impact\n\n2. **Autopilot enforces resource minimums:**\n   - CPU request minimum: 250m (can't go lower)\n   - Memory request minimum: 512Mi (can't go lower)\n   - If your pod only needs 10m CPU, you still pay for 250m\n\n3. **Autopilot adjusts resources upward:**\n   - If you set CPU request=250m but limit=4000m, Autopilot may increase the request to match internal bin-packing (not documented, but observed)\n   - If memory limit >> request, Autopilot may increase request\n\n4. **Burst-to-limit is NOT free:**\n   - In standard GKE, Burstable pods can use node slack for free\n   - In Autopilot, you're charged for the request, and limit represents the maximum allowed burst. But the burst capacity isn't guaranteed.\n\n**Right-sizing strategy for Autopilot:**\n\n1. **Set request = limit for predictable billing.** In Autopilot, Burstable QoS doesn't save money -- you pay for the request regardless. Set request=limit to get Guaranteed QoS and predictable performance.\n\n2. **Right-size to P95 + 20% headroom.** The minimum is 250m/512Mi, so very small sidecars and utility containers are over-provisioned by default.\n\n3. **Consolidate small containers.** If you have 3 sidecar containers each at 250m minimum, that's 750m of forced overhead. Consider:\n   - Removing unnecessary sidecars\n   - Using DaemonSets (which don't have Autopilot minimums)\n   - Combining functionality into the main container\n\n4. **Use Autopilot's built-in VPA.** Autopilot includes VPA recommendations. Check with:\n```bash\nkubectl get vpa -A\n```\n\n5. **Cost calculation:** `monthly_cost = (cpu_request * $0.0445/hr + memory_request_Gi * $0.0049/hr) * 730 hours`\nA pod with 1 CPU / 4Gi: ~$32.49 + $14.31 = $46.80/month\n\n**Autopilot-specific gotcha:** DaemonSet pods in Autopilot are free (Google absorbs the cost). This inverts the normal right-sizing priority -- DaemonSets are the cheapest place to put functionality in Autopilot.", "right-sizing", p),

        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-011",
            "We use EKS with Karpenter and a mix of spot and on-demand instances. How should right-sizing interact with Karpenter's node provisioning?",
            "## EKS + Karpenter Right-Sizing Strategy\n\n**Karpenter's unique behaviour changes right-sizing dynamics:**\n\nUnlike the cluster autoscaler (which scales fixed node groups), Karpenter selects the optimal instance type for each pending pod group. This creates a tight feedback loop between pod requests and node costs.\n\n**How right-sizing amplifies Karpenter savings:**\n\n1. **Smaller requests = more instance options.** A pod requesting 8Gi memory can only run on instances with 8Gi+ allocatable. A pod right-sized to 2Gi memory can run on m5.large (8Gi), m5.medium (4Gi), t3.small (2Gi), and dozens more types.\n\n2. **More instance options = better spot pricing.** Karpenter's spot diversification strategy works better with more eligible types. Right-sizing from 8Gi to 2Gi might expand from 5 eligible types to 30, reducing spot interruption risk and cost.\n\n3. **Consolidation improves.** Karpenter's consolidation moves pods to cheaper/smaller nodes. Right-sized pods consolidate more efficiently because they fit into smaller remaining capacity.\n\n**Practical workflow:**\n\n**Step 1: Right-size pods first**\n- Analyse all workloads using Prometheus metrics\n- Reduce requests to P95 + 20% headroom\n- Deploy changes\n\n**Step 2: Let Karpenter react**\n- Karpenter detects that existing nodes are under-utilised\n- Consolidation kicks in: moves pods to fewer, smaller nodes\n- Old over-sized nodes are terminated\n- New nodes are right-sized for the right-sized pods\n\n**Step 3: Verify instance types**\n```bash\n# Check what Karpenter selected\nkubectl get nodes -L node.kubernetes.io/instance-type,karpenter.sh/capacity-type\n```\nYou should see smaller instance types (m5.xlarge instead of m5.4xlarge) and more spot instances.\n\n**Karpenter NodePool configuration for right-sizing:**\n```yaml\napiVersion: karpenter.sh/v1beta1\nkind: NodePool\nspec:\n  template:\n    spec:\n      requirements:\n      - key: karpenter.sh/capacity-type\n        operator: In\n        values: [spot, on-demand]\n      - key: node.kubernetes.io/instance-type\n        operator: In\n        values:  # Include small types after right-sizing\n        - m5.large    # 2 CPU, 8Gi\n        - m5.xlarge   # 4 CPU, 16Gi\n        - m5.2xlarge  # 8 CPU, 32Gi\n        - c5.large    # 2 CPU, 4Gi (compute-optimised)\n        - r5.large    # 2 CPU, 16Gi (memory-optimised)\n  disruption:\n    consolidationPolicy: WhenUnderutilized\n    consolidateAfter: 30s\n```\n\n**Expected savings from right-sizing + Karpenter:**\n- Right-sizing alone: 30-40% cost reduction\n- Karpenter alone: 20-30% cost reduction\n- Combined: 40-60% cost reduction (they compound)\n\n**Monitoring:** Track `karpenter_nodes_total` and `karpenter_pods_per_node` after right-sizing. Pods-per-node should increase (better packing) and total nodes should decrease.", "right-sizing", p),
    ]


# ── JVM deep-dives ───────────────────────────────────────────────────

def jvm_deep_pairs():
    """JVM: ZGC vs Shenandoah, GraalVM native-image, class data sharing."""
    p = "expert-operational-knowledge"
    return [
        make_pair("expert-runtime-specific-015",
            "Workload: deployment/auth-service\nReplicas: 3\nContainer: ghcr.io/graalvm/native-image-community:17\nCPU Request: 500m, Limit: 1000m\nMemory Request: 256Mi, Limit: 512Mi\nCPU Usage (7d): P50=30m, P95=100m, P99=200m, Max=400m\nMemory Usage (7d): P50=80Mi, P95=100Mi, P99=120Mi, Max=150Mi\nStartup time: 50ms\nGraalVM native-image compiled Spring Boot application\nPattern: Burstable\nRestarts (7d): 0",
            "## Analysis\n\n**GraalVM native-image fundamentally changes JVM resource characteristics.** This is NOT a standard JVM workload.\n\n**Key differences from JVM:**\n1. **No JIT compilation**: All code is AOT-compiled. No warmup period, no code cache growth.\n2. **No class loading at runtime**: All classes are resolved at build time. Metaspace is minimal.\n3. **Substrate VM GC**: Uses Serial GC or G1GC, but with a much smaller footprint than HotSpot.\n4. **50ms startup**: vs 5-30 seconds for standard Spring Boot. This enables scale-to-zero.\n\n**Memory**: 80-150Mi is typical for a native-image Spring Boot app. Compare to 500Mi-2Gi for the same app on HotSpot JVM. The 3-10x memory reduction is the primary benefit.\n\n**CPU**: Native-image apps use less CPU at steady state (no JIT overhead) but may use more CPU for peak throughput (JIT-compiled hot paths are sometimes faster than AOT-compiled code).\n\n## Recommendations\n\n**CPU**: Request=120m (P95 * 1.20). Limit=500m (Max * 1.25).\n- Savings: 380m per pod = 1140m total\n\n**Memory**: Request=144Mi (P99 * 1.20). Limit=188Mi (Max * 1.25).\n- Savings: 112Mi per pod = 336Mi total\n\n**Native-image-specific notes:**\n\n1. **Memory is deterministic.** Unlike HotSpot where memory grows with JIT compilation and class loading, native-image memory is stable from startup. Right-sizing can be aggressive (P95 + 15% headroom instead of 20%).\n\n2. **No -Xmx needed.** Native-image manages its own heap. Use `-R:MaxHeapSize=128m` at build time to set the heap limit inside the native binary. The K8s memory limit should be MaxHeapSize + 30% for native memory overhead.\n\n3. **Startup probe can be very short.** With 50ms startup, set:\n```yaml\nstartupProbe:\n  httpGet: {path: /health, port: 8080}\n  failureThreshold: 3\n  periodSeconds: 1  # 3 seconds total\n```\n\n4. **Ideal for scale-to-zero (Knative/KEDA).** The 50ms startup eliminates cold-start latency. Scale to 0 replicas during idle periods for maximum savings.\n\n5. **Build-time resource usage** (not runtime): Native-image compilation is extremely resource-intensive. Building a Spring Boot native-image needs 8Gi+ memory and 4+ CPU for 5-15 minutes. Ensure CI/CD runners are sized for builds, not the runtime container.", "runtime-specific", p, runtime="jvm"),
    ]


