def temporal_worker_pairs():
    """Temporal/workflow engine workloads."""
    p = "expert-operational-knowledge"
    return [
        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-035",
            "Workload: deployment/temporal-worker\nReplicas: 10\nContainer: custom Go binary\nCPU Request: 2000m, Limit: 4000m\nMemory Request: 2Gi, Limit: 4Gi\nCPU Usage (7d): P50=500m, P95=1500m, P99=2500m, Max=3800m\nMemory Usage (7d): P50=400Mi, P95=600Mi, P99=800Mi, Max=1.2Gi\nTemporal: 1000 workflows/min, 50 activities/sec per worker\nGo workers: MaxConcurrentActivityExecutionSize=200, MaxConcurrentWorkflowTaskExecutionSize=100\nPattern: Steady with activity bursts\nRestarts (7d): 0",
            "## Analysis\n\n**Temporal workers are Go processes that execute workflow activities. Resource usage scales with concurrent activity execution.**\n\n**CPU**: Each activity execution is typically a function call that may make API calls, database queries, or compute transformations:\n- Idle polling: ~10m per worker (polling Temporal server for tasks)\n- Activity execution: varies wildly. Simple API call: 5-10m. Data transformation: 100-500m.\n- P95=1500m with 50 activities/sec: ~30m per activity average (I/O bound, mostly waiting)\n- Max=3800m: burst of CPU-intensive activities executing simultaneously\n\n**Memory**: Go binary + goroutine stacks:\n- Temporal SDK overhead: ~50Mi per worker\n- Per-activity goroutine: ~8KB stack. 200 concurrent: 1.6Mi\n- Activity payloads in memory: depends on data size. 200 activities * 1MB payload = 200Mi\n- Workflow state cache: 100 concurrent workflows * 50KB state = 5Mi\n- P50=400Mi: normal activity mix. Max=1.2Gi: large payload activities.\n\n## Recommendations\n\n**CPU**: Request=1800m (P95 * 1.20). Limit=4000m (keep).\n- Savings: 200m per pod = 2000m total\n\n**Memory**: Request=960Mi (P99 * 1.20). Limit=1.5Gi (Max * 1.25).\n- Savings: 1040Mi per pod = 10.4Gi total\n\n**Temporal-specific tuning:**\n1. **Reduce MaxConcurrentActivityExecutionSize**: From 200 to 100. Each concurrent activity holds memory for payload + goroutine. Halving concurrency halves memory spikes but may reduce throughput. Test with actual workload.\n2. **Activity heartbeat timeout**: Long-running activities without heartbeats hold resources. Set short heartbeat timeouts to detect stuck activities.\n3. **Worker count vs concurrency**: Better to have 10 workers * 100 concurrent activities than 5 workers * 200. More workers = better distribution, more failure domains.\n4. **Set GOMEMLIMIT**: `GOMEMLIMIT=1200000000` (1.2Gi, 80% of limit). Prevents Go heap from growing into limit.\n5. **Task queue routing**: Route CPU-intensive activities to a dedicated worker pool with higher CPU limits. Route I/O-bound activities to a pool with more concurrency but lower CPU.", "right-sizing", p, runtime="go"),
    ]


def keycloak_pairs():
    """Identity/auth: Keycloak, OAuth proxies."""
    p = "expert-operational-knowledge"
    return [
        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-036",
            "Workload: statefulset/keycloak\nReplicas: 2\nContainer: quay.io/keycloak/keycloak:23\nJVM: -Xmx512m -Xms512m\nCPU Request: 2000m, Limit: 4000m\nMemory Request: 2Gi, Limit: 4Gi\nCPU Usage: P50=100m, P95=500m, P99=1000m, Max=3000m\nMemory Usage: P50=700Mi, P95=800Mi, P99=900Mi, Max=1.2Gi\nUsers: 10,000 registered, 500 concurrent sessions\nRealms: 3, clients: 50\nPattern: Burstable (login spikes at 9 AM)\nRestarts (7d): 0",
            "## Analysis\n\n**Keycloak is a JVM-based (Quarkus since v17) identity provider. Its CPU pattern is login-event-driven.**\n\n**CPU**: Authentication events are CPU-intensive:\n- Password hashing (bcrypt): ~100m per login (bcrypt is intentionally slow for security)\n- Token generation (RSA/EC signing): ~5m per token\n- Token validation (signature verification): ~2m per validation\n- P50=100m: Background session management, health checks\n- Max=3000m: Morning login spike. 500 users * bcrypt = significant CPU\n- OIDC/SAML assertions: 10-50m each depending on claims\n\n**Memory**: JVM heap (512m) + Quarkus native memory:\n- Heap: 512Mi (user sessions, realm caches, client configs)\n- Infinispan cache (embedded): Session cache for 500 sessions * 5KB = 2.5Mi\n- Metaspace: ~100Mi (Quarkus is better than Spring but still has class loading)\n- Native memory (Netty, SSL, IO): ~100-200Mi\n- Total: 512Mi heap + 300Mi native = ~800Mi (matches P50=700Mi)\n\n## Recommendations\n\n**CPU**: Request=600m (P95 * 1.20). Limit=3750m (Max * 1.25).\n- Savings: 1400m per pod = 2800m total\n\n**Memory**: Request=1.08Gi (P99 * 1.20). Limit=1.5Gi (Max * 1.25).\n- Savings: 920Mi per pod = 1.84Gi total\n\n**Keycloak-specific tuning:**\n1. **Increase -Xmx for large session counts**: 512m is tight for 500 concurrent sessions. With 5000 sessions: -Xmx=1g. Formula: 512m base + 2KB per active session.\n2. **External Infinispan**: For HA across replicas, use external Infinispan cluster. Removes session replication memory from Keycloak pods.\n3. **bcrypt work factor**: Default work factor = 12 (intentionally CPU-heavy). If CPU spikes are unacceptable, reduce to 10 (4x faster) but less secure. Trade-off between security and resource usage.\n4. **Token caching**: Enable Keycloak's token endpoint cache. Reduces repeated token validation CPU by 50-70%.\n5. **Quarkus vs WildFly**: Keycloak 17+ uses Quarkus (faster startup, less memory). If running <17, upgrade for 30-40% memory reduction.", "right-sizing", p, runtime="jvm"),
    ]


def network_tools_pairs():
    """Network tools: service mesh, ingress controllers."""
    p = "expert-operational-knowledge"
    return [
        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-037",
            "Workload: daemonset/istio-proxy (Envoy sidecars injected into all pods)\nTotal sidecars: 200 (one per application pod)\nCPU Request per sidecar: 100m, Limit: 2000m\nMemory Request per sidecar: 128Mi, Limit: 1Gi\nSidecar CPU Usage: P50=10m, P95=50m, P99=100m, Max=500m\nSidecar Memory Usage: P50=60Mi, P95=80Mi, P99=100Mi, Max=200Mi\n\nTotal Istio sidecar overhead: CPU=20000m request, Memory=25.6Gi request across 200 pods.",
            "## Analysis\n\n**Istio sidecar resource overhead is the #1 hidden cost in service mesh deployments.** With 200 sidecars at default requests, the mesh infrastructure costs more than many application workloads.\n\n**CPU**: 200 sidecars * 100m request = 20,000m = 20 full CPU cores allocated just for proxies.\nActual usage: 200 * 50m P95 = 10,000m. 50% waste on requests alone.\n\n**Memory**: 200 sidecars * 128Mi request = 25.6Gi.\nActual usage: 200 * 80Mi P95 = 16Gi. 37.5% waste.\n\n## Recommendations\n\n**Global sidecar resource override in Istio:**\n```yaml\napiVersion: install.istio.io/v1alpha1\nkind: IstioOperator\nspec:\n  meshConfig:\n    defaultConfig:\n      proxyMetadata:\n        ISTIO_META_REQUESTED_NETWORK_VIEW: \"standard\"\n  values:\n    global:\n      proxy:\n        resources:\n          requests:\n            cpu: 20m       # Down from 100m\n            memory: 64Mi   # Down from 128Mi\n          limits:\n            cpu: 500m      # Down from 2000m\n            memory: 256Mi  # Down from 1Gi\n```\n\n**Per-pod override for high-traffic services:**\n```yaml\napiVersion: v1\nkind: Pod\nmetadata:\n  annotations:\n    sidecar.istio.io/proxyCPU: \"50m\"\n    sidecar.istio.io/proxyCPULimit: \"1000m\"\n    sidecar.istio.io/proxyMemory: \"128Mi\"\n    sidecar.istio.io/proxyMemoryLimit: \"512Mi\"\n```\n\n**Savings calculation:**\n| | Before | After | Savings |\n|---|--------|-------|--------|\n| CPU request (total) | 20,000m | 4,000m | 16,000m |\n| Memory request (total) | 25.6Gi | 12.8Gi | 12.8Gi |\n\n**That's 16 CPU cores and 12.8Gi freed across the cluster.**\n\n**Istio-specific considerations:**\n1. **Sidecar discovery scope**: By default, every sidecar receives the full cluster service mesh configuration. Use `Sidecar` resource to limit scope. Reduces memory from 80Mi to 30Mi per sidecar.\n2. **mTLS overhead**: mTLS adds ~2-5% CPU overhead per connection for TLS handshake. More connections = more sidecar CPU.\n3. **Ambient mesh (Istio 1.22+)**: Replaces sidecars with per-node ztunnel. One proxy per node instead of per pod. 200 sidecars → 10 ztunnels = 95% reduction in proxy resource overhead.\n4. **Protocol detection**: Istio's protocol sniffing adds latency and memory. Explicitly declare `appProtocol: http` or `appProtocol: tcp` on Service ports.\n5. **Access logging**: Disable access logging for non-production or low-value services. Each log entry consumes CPU and memory in the sidecar.", "right-sizing", p, runtime="generic"),

        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-038",
            "Workload: deployment/nginx-ingress-controller\nReplicas: 3\nContainer: nginx/nginx-ingress:3.4\nCPU Request: 2000m, Limit: 4000m\nMemory Request: 2Gi, Limit: 4Gi\nCPU Usage: P50=200m, P95=1000m, P99=2000m, Max=3500m\nMemory Usage: P50=300Mi, P95=500Mi, P99=700Mi, Max=1.2Gi\nIngress rules: 500\nTLS termination: 80% of traffic\nRPS: 50,000 peak across all ingresses\nConnections: 20,000 concurrent\nPattern: Burstable (traffic correlated)\nRestarts (7d): 0",
            "## Analysis\n\n**Nginx ingress controller resource usage is driven by: (1) TLS operations, (2) connection count, (3) configuration complexity.**\n\n**CPU**: At 50K RPS peak:\n- TLS termination: 80% of 50K = 40K TLS requests. At ~0.02ms CPU per TLS record: ~800m\n- TLS handshakes (new connections): ~1ms per handshake. At 2000 new/sec: ~2000m\n- Upstream proxying: ~0.005ms per request: ~250m\n- Lua/OpenResty plugins (if any): varies. Rate limiting, auth: ~200m\n- nginx config reload (when Ingress resources change): brief spike to 1000m+\n\n**Memory**: \n- Worker processes: 4 workers (default = CPU count) * 50Mi each = 200Mi\n- Connection state: 20,000 * 5KB = 100Mi\n- TLS session cache: configurable, default ~50Mi\n- Upstream keepalive pools: 500 upstreams * 10 keepalive connections * 1KB = 5Mi\n- Shared memory zones (rate limiting, caching): configurable\n\n## Recommendations\n\n**CPU**: Request=1200m (P95 * 1.20). Limit=4000m (keep).\n- Savings: 800m per pod = 2400m total\n\n**Memory**: Request=840Mi (P99 * 1.20). Limit=1.5Gi (Max * 1.25).\n- Savings: 1160Mi per pod = 3480Mi total\n\n**Nginx-specific tuning:**\n1. **worker_processes auto**: Set to CPU limit, not auto (which reads node CPUs). With limit=4: `worker_processes 4`.\n2. **TLS session tickets**: Enable `ssl_session_tickets on` with rotated keys. Clients resume sessions without CPU-expensive handshakes. 50-80% reduction in TLS CPU.\n3. **Connection keepalive**: `keepalive_timeout 65s` and `upstream keepalive 100` per upstream. Reduces new connection rate.\n4. **Config reload impact**: Every Ingress change triggers nginx config reload. In clusters with frequent deployments (50+ per day), consider batching Ingress changes or using the Nginx+ version with API-based config updates.\n5. **HPA for ingress**: Scale based on custom metric `nginx_ingress_controller_requests` or `nginx_connections_active`. CPU-based HPA works poorly because CPU spikes are brief.", "right-sizing", p, runtime="generic"),
    ]


def jvm_tuning_pairs():
    """JVM: heap sizing formula, container awareness, startup."""
    p = "expert-operational-knowledge"
    return [
        make_pair("expert-runtime-specific-026",
            "What is the correct formula for setting JVM heap size (-Xmx) relative to the Kubernetes container memory limit?",
            "## JVM Heap Sizing Formula for Kubernetes\n\n**The container memory limit must cover JVM heap + all non-heap memory.**\n\n**JVM memory components:**\n```\nContainer memory = JVM Heap (-Xmx)\n                 + Metaspace (class metadata)\n                 + Thread stacks (per thread)\n                 + Code cache (JIT compiled code)\n                 + Direct buffers (NIO)\n                 + GC overhead\n                 + Native memory (JNI, C libraries)\n                 + Mapped files\n```\n\n**Typical non-heap overhead:**\n\n| Component | Estimate | Notes |\n|-----------|----------|-------|\n| Metaspace | 100-300Mi | Spring Boot: 200-300Mi. Quarkus: 50-100Mi |\n| Thread stacks | threads * 1Mi | Default -Xss1m. 200 threads = 200Mi |\n| Code cache | 50-250Mi | -XX:ReservedCodeCacheSize default: 240Mi |\n| Direct buffers | 0-500Mi | Netty, gRPC, file I/O |\n| GC overhead | heap * 0.10-0.25 | G1GC: 10-15%. ZGC: 20-25% |\n| Native | 50-200Mi | JNI, OpenSSL, compression |\n| **Total non-heap** | **500Mi-2Gi** | Depends on application |\n\n**Formula:**\n```\ncontainer_limit = heap + non_heap_overhead + 20% safety margin\n\nOR equivalently:\nhap = container_limit * percentage\n```\n\n**Recommended percentages:**\n\n| Scenario | -Xmx as % of limit | Example (2Gi limit) |\n|----------|-------------------|--------------------|\n| Simple microservice (few threads, no NIO) | 75% | -Xmx=1536m |\n| Spring Boot web service | 65% | -Xmx=1331m |\n| Netty/gRPC service (heavy NIO) | 55% | -Xmx=1126m |\n| Big data processing (Spark, Flink) | 50% | -Xmx=1024m |\n\n**Modern approach: -XX:MaxRAMPercentage**\n```\n-XX:MaxRAMPercentage=65.0  # JVM calculates Xmx as 65% of container limit\n-XX:InitialRAMPercentage=65.0  # Start with this percentage\n-XX:MinRAMPercentage=50.0  # Floor for small containers\n```\n\nAdvantages:\n- Automatically adapts if you change the container memory limit\n- No need to manually calculate and coordinate -Xmx with resource limits\n- Works correctly with container-aware JVM (Java 10+)\n\n**Critical rules:**\n1. NEVER set -Xmx > 75% of container limit (guaranteed OOM)\n2. NEVER set -Xmx > 30.5Gi (loses CompressedOops, wastes heap)\n3. ALWAYS set -Xms = -Xmx in containers (avoid lazy allocation, memory accounting is immediate)\n4. ALWAYS verify with: `java -XX:+PrintFlagsFinal -version | grep -i heapsize`\n5. If OOMKilled despite low heap usage: monitor native memory with `-XX:NativeMemoryTracking=summary`", "runtime-specific", p, runtime="jvm"),

        make_pair("expert-edge-case-029",
            "Our Java Spring Boot service takes 45 seconds to start. During startup, CPU spikes to 8000m and memory grows from 0 to 1.5Gi. After startup, it uses 200m CPU and 1.5Gi memory (steady). How should I configure resource requests and startup probes?",
            "## Analysis\n\n**JVM startup resource profile is radically different from steady-state.** Spring Boot startup involves:\n\n1. **Class loading** (0-15s): Load thousands of classes. CPU-intensive (I/O + class verification). Memory grows as classes are loaded into Metaspace.\n2. **Dependency injection** (5-20s): Spring creates and wires beans. CPU-intensive (reflection, proxy generation).\n3. **JIT compilation** (10-45s): HotSpot's C1 and C2 compilers compile hot methods. Massive CPU spike. This is why CPU goes to 8000m.\n4. **Connection pool warmup** (5-10s): Database connections, HTTP client pools.\n\n**After startup**: JIT compilation is done, class loading is done. CPU drops to 200m (handling requests). Memory stabilises at 1.5Gi.\n\n## Recommendations\n\n**Resource configuration:**\n```yaml\nresources:\n  requests:\n    cpu: 240m      # Steady-state P95 * 1.20\n    memory: 1.8Gi  # Steady-state P99 * 1.20\n  limits:\n    cpu: 8000m     # Startup needs full burst\n    memory: 2Gi    # Startup memory + headroom\n```\n\n**Why low CPU request + high limit:**\n- Request=240m: Scheduler allocates for steady-state. Efficient bin-packing.\n- Limit=8000m: During 45s startup, the container CAN burst to 8000m if node has capacity.\n- Burstable QoS: Good trade-off for services with startup spikes.\n\n**Startup probe configuration:**\n```yaml\nstartupProbe:\n  httpGet:\n    path: /actuator/health\n    port: 8080\n  initialDelaySeconds: 10    # Spring needs 10s before health endpoint is up\n  periodSeconds: 5           # Check every 5 seconds\n  failureThreshold: 12       # 10 + (12 * 5) = 70 seconds max startup time\n  timeoutSeconds: 3\n\nreadinessProbe:\n  httpGet:\n    path: /actuator/health/readiness\n    port: 8080\n  periodSeconds: 10\n  failureThreshold: 3\n\nlivenessProbe:\n  httpGet:\n    path: /actuator/health/liveness\n    port: 8080\n  periodSeconds: 30          # Longer period for liveness (don't restart on brief issues)\n  failureThreshold: 3\n  initialDelaySeconds: 0     # startupProbe handles initial delay\n```\n\n**Reducing startup time (reduces the resource spike):**\n1. **Spring Boot lazy initialization**: `spring.main.lazy-initialization=true`. Beans created on first use, not startup. Startup: 45s → 15s. Trade-off: first request is slower.\n2. **JVM tiered compilation**: `-XX:TieredStopAtLevel=1` during startup (C1 only, no C2 optimisation). Startup: 45s → 25s. Trade-off: slightly less throughput.\n3. **Spring AOT (Spring 6.0+)**: Ahead-of-time compilation reduces reflection at startup. Startup: 45s → 20s.\n4. **Class Data Sharing (CDS)**: `-XX:SharedArchiveFile=app.jsa` — pre-compiled class metadata. Saves 5-15s of class loading.\n5. **GraalVM native-image**: Eliminates JVM startup entirely. 45s → 50ms. But requires build-time class analysis and may not support all Spring features.", "edge-case", p, runtime="jvm"),
    ]


def python_patterns_pairs():
    """Python-specific: memory management, multiprocessing, async patterns."""
    p = "expert-operational-knowledge"
    return [
        make_pair("expert-runtime-specific-027",
            "Workload: deployment/data-api\nReplicas: 4\nContainer: python:3.11\nCPU Request: 2000m, Limit: 4000m\nMemory Request: 4Gi, Limit: 8Gi\nCPU Usage: P50=400m, P95=1500m, P99=2500m, Max=3800m\nMemory Usage: P50=2Gi, P95=2.5Gi, P99=3Gi, Max=4.5Gi\nGunicorn: 4 workers, sync worker class\nDjango + pandas for data transformations\nPattern: Burstable\nRestarts (7d): 1 (OOMKilled)",
            "## Analysis\n\n**Python + pandas is one of the most challenging combinations for right-sizing** because pandas eagerly loads data into memory and Python's memory allocator never releases memory back to the OS.\n\n**Memory**: 4 Gunicorn workers (sync), each a separate process:\n- Python interpreter: ~30Mi per worker\n- Django framework: ~100Mi per worker\n- pandas + numpy shared libraries: ~150Mi (shared via CoW after fork)\n- Per-request data frames: THIS IS THE VARIABLE. A single `pd.read_sql()` for 1M rows * 20 columns * 8 bytes = 160Mi per DataFrame. With copies during transformation: 320Mi.\n- 4 workers processing simultaneously: 4 * 320Mi = 1.28Gi of DataFrame memory\n- Plus baseline: 150Mi + 4 * 130Mi = 670Mi\n- Total peak: 670Mi + 1.28Gi ≈ 1.95Gi per pod\n\n**Why memory never decreases (P50=2Gi):**\nCPython's pymalloc allocator: small objects (<512 bytes) are allocated in pools. Pools are only returned to the OS when ALL objects in the pool are freed. With pandas creating millions of small objects, some pools always have at least one live object → memory never decreases.\n\n**OOMKill cause**: A large query created multiple DataFrames simultaneously (join operation): 3-4x the single DataFrame size = 1.28Gi * 3 = 3.84Gi + baseline = 4.5Gi → exceeded memory under concurrent load.\n\n## Recommendations\n\n**CPU**: Request=1800m (P95 * 1.20). Limit=4000m (keep).\n- Savings: 200m per pod = 800m total\n\n**Memory**: Request=3.6Gi (P99 * 1.20). Limit=5.625Gi (Max * 1.25).\n- Savings: 2.375Gi limit per pod = 9.5Gi total\n\n**Python-specific tuning:**\n1. **Chunk processing**: Replace `pd.read_sql(query)` with `pd.read_sql(query, chunksize=10000)`. Process in chunks instead of loading entire result set. Memory per chunk: 160Mi / 100 = 1.6Mi.\n2. **Worker recycling**: Set `--max-requests 500` on Gunicorn. Workers restart after 500 requests, releasing all accumulated memory. Brief latency spike during restart.\n3. **Use gunicorn --preload**: Loads Django + pandas in the parent process. Workers share via CoW. Saves ~100Mi per worker.\n4. **Alternative to pandas**: Use Polars (Rust-based, 2-5x less memory) or DuckDB (SQL on DataFrame, columnar storage, streaming). Polars doesn't have the Python allocator issue.\n5. **Memory limit per request**: Set Django middleware to reject requests that would process >100K rows. Or use streaming responses instead of building full DataFrames.", "runtime-specific", p, runtime="python"),

        make_pair("expert-runtime-specific-028",
            "How does Python's multiprocessing interact with container memory limits? We keep getting OOMKilled when using multiprocessing.Pool(processes=8) in a container with 4Gi limit.",
            "## Python multiprocessing and Container Memory\n\n**multiprocessing.Pool(processes=8) creates 8 CHILD PROCESSES, each with their own memory space. Total memory = parent + 8 children.**\n\n**The problem:**\n- Parent process: 500Mi (Python + loaded libraries + data)\n- Fork creates 8 children via `os.fork()`\n- Immediately after fork: 8 children share parent memory via Copy-on-Write (CoW)\n- Memory: 500Mi parent + 0 (CoW) = 500Mi total\n\n**But then children start working:**\n- Each child imports modules, allocates data, runs computations\n- CoW pages diverge: each child gets unique pages\n- After divergence: each child holds 300-500Mi of unique memory\n- Total: 500Mi parent + 8 * 400Mi children = 3.7Gi\n- Plus Python overhead, GC: approaching 4Gi limit\n- If children create DataFrames or load data: each child may need 500Mi+\n- 500Mi parent + 8 * 600Mi = 5.3Gi → OOMKill at 4Gi\n\n## Solutions\n\n**1. Reduce worker count to match memory budget:**\n```python\nimport os\ndef get_optimal_workers(per_worker_memory_mi, safety_margin=0.8):\n    # Read container memory limit from cgroup\n    with open('/sys/fs/cgroup/memory.max') as f:\n        limit_bytes = int(f.read().strip())\n    limit_mi = limit_bytes / (1024 * 1024)\n    parent_mi = 500  # estimated parent memory\n    available = (limit_mi * safety_margin) - parent_mi\n    return max(1, int(available / per_worker_memory_mi))\n\n# Usage: 4Gi limit, 500Mi per worker\nworkers = get_optimal_workers(500)  # Returns 5\npool = multiprocessing.Pool(processes=workers)\n```\n\n**2. Use 'spawn' start method instead of 'fork':**\n```python\nimport multiprocessing\nmultiprocessing.set_start_method('spawn')  # Don't copy parent memory\n```\n- 'fork': children copy parent memory (CoW). Fast start, high memory.\n- 'spawn': children start fresh Python interpreter. Slow start, predictable memory.\n- 'forkserver': Hybrid. Fork from a lean server process.\n\n**3. Use process pools with maxtasksperchild:**\n```python\npool = multiprocessing.Pool(processes=4, maxtasksperchild=100)\n```\nWorkers restart after 100 tasks, releasing accumulated memory.\n\n**4. Shared memory for large data:**\n```python\nimport numpy as np\nfrom multiprocessing import shared_memory\n\nshm = shared_memory.SharedMemory(create=True, size=data.nbytes)\nnp_array = np.ndarray(data.shape, dtype=data.dtype, buffer=shm.buf)\n```\nOne copy of data shared across all workers. Memory: data_size + N * per_worker_overhead.\n\n**Right-sizing for multiprocessing:**\n```\ncontainer_limit = parent_memory + (num_workers * per_worker_memory) + 20% headroom\n```\nWith 4 workers * 500Mi + 500Mi parent + 20%: limit = 3.6Gi. Set to 4Gi.\n\n**Do NOT set num_workers = os.cpu_count() in containers.** This reads NODE CPU count (e.g., 64 cores), not container limit. Use: `min(os.cpu_count(), int(os.environ.get('CPU_LIMIT', 4)))`.", "runtime-specific", p, runtime="python"),
    ]


def node_patterns_pairs():
    """Node.js patterns: cluster module, worker threads, memory leaks."""
    p = "expert-operational-knowledge"
    return [
        make_pair("expert-runtime-specific-029",
            "We're running a Node.js service with the cluster module (4 worker processes) in a container with 2 CPU limit. Is this optimal?",
            "## Node.js Cluster Module and Container CPU Limits\n\n**The cluster module creates N worker processes, each running a full Node.js/V8 instance.** With 4 workers on a 2-CPU limit, you have 4 processes competing for 2 CPUs.\n\n**The problem:**\n- Each Node.js worker is single-threaded for JS execution\n- 4 workers = 4 OS processes = can use up to 4 CPUs simultaneously\n- But CFS limit = 200ms per 100ms period (2 CPUs)\n- If all 4 workers are active: 4 * 25ms = 100ms CPU in 25ms wall-clock → throttled for 75ms\n- 75% CFS throttling during concurrent request processing\n\n**Optimal worker count formula:**\n```\nworkers = Math.floor(CPU_limit_in_cores)\n```\n- 2 CPU limit → 2 workers (each gets 1 full core equivalent)\n- 4 CPU limit → 4 workers\n- 1 CPU limit → 1 worker (cluster module adds overhead for 1 worker; skip it)\n\n**Memory impact:**\n- Each worker: V8 isolate (60Mi) + loaded modules (20-100Mi) + request buffers\n- 4 workers * 100Mi = 400Mi for V8 overhead alone\n- 2 workers * 100Mi = 200Mi — saves 200Mi and eliminates throttling\n\n## Recommendations\n\n**Reduce to 2 workers:**\n```javascript\nconst cluster = require('cluster');\nconst numWorkers = Math.floor(parseFloat(process.env.CPU_LIMIT || '2'));\n\nif (cluster.isPrimary) {\n  for (let i = 0; i < numWorkers; i++) {\n    cluster.fork();\n  }\n} else {\n  startServer();\n}\n```\n\n**Set --max-old-space-size per worker:**\n```\n--max-old-space-size=$((MEMORY_LIMIT_MI / NUM_WORKERS - 60))\n```\nWith 2Gi limit, 2 workers: --max-old-space-size=900 (1024Mi - 60Mi overhead per worker, leave 128Mi for primary + OS).\n\n**Alternative: Worker Threads instead of Cluster:**\n```javascript\nconst { Worker } = require('worker_threads');\n```\n- Worker Threads share the same process memory (lower overhead)\n- Good for CPU-intensive tasks (image processing, crypto)\n- Not a replacement for Cluster for request isolation\n- Memory overhead: 20-40Mi per thread vs 60-100Mi per worker process\n\n**Right-sizing:**\n- CPU: Request = steady_per_worker * num_workers. 200m * 2 = 400m request.\n- Memory: Request = per_worker_overhead * num_workers + shared. 150Mi * 2 + 100Mi = 400Mi request.\n- Limit CPU: num_workers * 1000m = 2000m (1 core per worker max burst).", "runtime-specific", p, runtime="node"),

        make_pair("expert-edge-case-030",
            "Our Node.js service memory grows by 50Mi per hour, every hour, consistently. After 24 hours it hits the 2Gi limit and gets OOMKilled. Is this a memory leak and how do I find it?",
            "## Analysis\n\n**50Mi/hour consistent growth is almost certainly a memory leak.** Normal Node.js memory oscillates with GC cycles (grows, GC collects, drops, grows again). Linear growth that never decreases = objects accumulating that GC can't collect.\n\n**Common Node.js memory leak patterns:**\n\n1. **Event listener accumulation (most common):**\n```javascript\n// LEAKY: Adding listener on every request\napp.get('/data', (req, res) => {\n  eventEmitter.on('update', handler); // Never removed!\n});\n// FIX: Remove listener when done\neventEmitter.once('update', handler); // Auto-removes\n```\n\n2. **Global cache without eviction:**\n```javascript\nconst cache = {}; // Grows forever\nfunction getData(key) {\n  if (!cache[key]) cache[key] = fetchFromDB(key);\n  return cache[key];\n}\n// FIX: Use LRU cache with maxSize\nconst { LRUCache } = require('lru-cache');\nconst cache = new LRUCache({ max: 1000 });\n```\n\n3. **Closure holding references:**\n```javascript\n// LEAKY: closure captures large object\nfunction processRequest(req) {\n  const largeData = loadLargeDataset();\n  return () => largeData.summary; // Holds entire dataset in memory\n}\n```\n\n4. **Uncleared timers/intervals:**\n```javascript\nsetInterval(() => { /* ... */ }, 1000); // Never cleared\n```\n\n## Diagnosis Steps\n\n**1. Heap snapshot comparison:**\n```bash\n# Take snapshot at start\ncurl http://pod:9229/json # Chrome DevTools Protocol\n# Or use --inspect flag and Chrome DevTools:\nnode --inspect=0.0.0.0:9229 app.js\n```\nTake heap snapshot at 1h and 2h. Compare: objects that grew = leak source.\n\n**2. Process.memoryUsage() monitoring:**\n```javascript\nsetInterval(() => {\n  const mem = process.memoryUsage();\n  console.log(JSON.stringify({\n    rss: (mem.rss / 1024 / 1024).toFixed(1) + 'Mi',\n    heapUsed: (mem.heapUsed / 1024 / 1024).toFixed(1) + 'Mi',\n    heapTotal: (mem.heapTotal / 1024 / 1024).toFixed(1) + 'Mi',\n    external: (mem.external / 1024 / 1024).toFixed(1) + 'Mi',\n  }));\n}, 60000);\n```\nIf `heapUsed` grows: JS object leak. If `external` grows: native addon leak. If `rss` grows but heap is stable: native memory leak (Buffer, streams).\n\n**Right-sizing while fixing the leak:**\n- Temporary: Increase limit to 3Gi AND add `--max-old-space-size=2048` to force V8 GC before OOM\n- Set pod restart policy with livenessProbe on memory usage\n- Add `max_old_space_size` that's 80% of container limit\n- Fix the leak (permanent solution)", "edge-case", p, runtime="node"),
    ]


def miscellaneous_expert_pairs():
    """Miscellaneous: DaemonSet sizing, GPU, ephemeral containers."""
    p = "expert-operational-knowledge"
    return [
        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-039",
            "How should DaemonSet resources be sized differently from Deployments? Our monitoring DaemonSet (node_exporter + custom agent) runs on every node.",
            "## DaemonSet Right-Sizing\n\n**DaemonSets have unique sizing considerations because they run on EVERY node and their resource usage is node-dependent, not traffic-dependent.**\n\n**Key differences from Deployment sizing:**\n\n1. **Fixed count**: You can't reduce replicas. 50 nodes = 50 DaemonSet pods. The ONLY way to reduce total footprint is per-pod right-sizing.\n\n2. **Node-proportional usage**: A DaemonSet on a 96-CPU node with 200 pods may use 5x the resources of the same DaemonSet on a 4-CPU node with 10 pods.\n\n3. **Impact on all nodes**: Over-provisioned DaemonSet requests reduce allocatable capacity on EVERY node.\n\n4. **Scheduling guarantee**: DaemonSets are typically system-critical. Under-provisioning can affect all workloads on every node.\n\n**Right-sizing approach for DaemonSets:**\n\n**Step 1: Measure across node types**\n```promql\n# CPU P95 per node type\nquantile_over_time(0.95,\n  rate(container_cpu_usage_seconds_total{pod=~\"node-exporter.*\"}[5m])[7d:5m]\n) by (node)\n```\n\nIf usage varies significantly by node size:\n```\nSmall nodes (4 CPU): P95=20m\nLarge nodes (96 CPU): P95=200m\n```\n\n**Step 2: Size for the LARGEST node**\nDaemonSet spec is uniform — same resources on all nodes. Size for the maximum.\n- Request: 240m (large node P95 * 1.20)\n- Limit: proportional to node size → BUT you can't vary limits in a DaemonSet\n\n**Step 3: Consider the total cluster impact**\n```\nTotal DaemonSet overhead = per_pod_request * node_count\n```\n50 nodes * 240m CPU = 12,000m = 12 full CPUs allocated to monitoring.\n\n**Optimization strategies:**\n\n1. **node_exporter is tiny**: Typical usage: 5-20m CPU, 20-40Mi memory. Default requests of 100m/200Mi are 5-10x over-provisioned. Set: requests={cpu: 20m, memory: 40Mi}, limits={cpu: 200m, memory: 100Mi}.\n\n2. **Use Guaranteed QoS for DaemonSets**: Set request=limit. DaemonSets should never be evicted — they provide critical node-level functionality.\n\n3. **Separate DaemonSets by function**: Don't combine node_exporter + fluent-bit + falco into one pod. Each has different resource profiles and lifecycle requirements.\n\n4. **GKE Autopilot**: DaemonSet pods are FREE (Google absorbs the cost). Over-provisioning DaemonSets on Autopilot has zero cost impact.\n\n5. **Tolerate ALL taints**: DaemonSets should run everywhere. Add tolerations for all taints to ensure monitoring covers all nodes.\n\n**Total cluster DaemonSet overhead audit:**\n```promql\nsum by (daemonset) (\n  kube_pod_container_resource_requests{resource=\"cpu\", created_by_kind=\"DaemonSet\"}\n)\n```\nIn a typical cluster, DaemonSets consume 10-25% of total cluster capacity. Right-sizing this alone frees 5-15% of cluster resources.", "right-sizing", p),

        make_pair("expert-edge-case-031",
            "We have a statefulset where memory usage is 95% of the limit at steady state. VPA recommends increasing the limit. But the application (Elasticsearch) deliberately uses all available memory for caching. How do I distinguish between 'needs more memory' and 'efficiently using available memory'?",
            "## The Cache-Aware Right-Sizing Problem\n\n**Some applications expand to fill available memory by design. Elasticsearch, Redis, PostgreSQL, and any application with in-memory caching will show 90-95% memory usage regardless of how much you allocate.** This is NOT the same as being under-provisioned.\n\n**How to distinguish:**\n\n**Signal 1: Does the application have configurable cache size?**\n- Elasticsearch: `indices.fielddata.cache.size` — fixed cache allocation\n- PostgreSQL: `shared_buffers` — fixed allocation\n- Redis: `maxmemory` — fixed allocation\n- Application LRU cache: typically configured with max size\n\nIf YES: the application uses `configured_cache + overhead`. Memory limit should be `cache_size + overhead + 20%`. It will always show high usage because the cache fills up.\n\n**Signal 2: Memory increases but performance is stable**\nIf you increase the limit from 8Gi to 16Gi and:\n- Memory usage rises from 7.5Gi to 15Gi (fills the new space)\n- Query latency is UNCHANGED\n- Throughput is UNCHANGED\n→ The application is caching more data but doesn't NEED it. The extra cache is beneficial but not required.\n\n**Signal 3: Page cache vs application memory**\nFor databases:\n```promql\ncontainer_memory_working_set_bytes - container_memory_rss\n```\nIf this delta is large (>20% of total): the extra memory is OS page cache, not application heap. Page cache is automatically reclaimed under pressure — it's NOT a reason to increase limits.\n\n**Signal 4: Application-specific health indicators**\n- Elasticsearch: `indices.cache.hit_rate` — if >90%, cache is effective. More memory = marginally higher hit rate but not required.\n- PostgreSQL: `pg_stat_user_tables.idx_scan / seq_scan` — if ratio is stable, shared_buffers is sufficient.\n- Redis: `keyspace_hits / (keyspace_hits + keyspace_misses)` — hit rate. If >95%, memory is sufficient.\n\n## Right-Sizing Decision Framework\n\n| Indicator | Needs more memory | Efficiently caching |\n|-----------|-------------------|--------------------|\n| OOMKills | Yes | No |\n| Eviction rate | High | Low or zero |\n| Performance after limit increase | Improves | Unchanged |\n| Memory usage pattern | Grows and crashes | Fills and stabilises |\n| Cache hit rate | Low (<80%) | High (>95%) |\n\n**For Elasticsearch specifically:**\n- Set memory limit = JVM heap * 2 (50% rule)\n- The remaining 50% IS the OS page cache\n- Elasticsearch at 95% memory usage with good search latency = correctly sized\n- Only increase if search latency degrades or GC pauses increase\n\n**VPA recommendation for cache-heavy apps:**\nVPA sees 95% usage and recommends increase. Override with:\n```yaml\nresourcePolicy:\n  containerPolicies:\n  - containerName: elasticsearch\n    maxAllowed:\n      memory: 32Gi  # Hard cap to prevent unbounded increase\n    controlledResources: [\"cpu\"]  # Let VPA manage CPU only\n```", "edge-case", p, runtime="generic"),

        make_pair("expert-classification-007",
            "How do I classify and right-size a workload that has two distinct patterns: steady during business hours (9-5) and batch processing overnight?",
            "## Multi-Modal Workload Classification\n\n**This is a bi-modal workload — it doesn't fit cleanly into steady, burstable, or batch. It's BOTH.**\n\n**The problem with standard classification:**\n- 7-day P95 averages together the day and night patterns\n- Day: CPU P95=500m (steady API traffic)\n- Night: CPU P95=4000m (batch processing)\n- Combined 7-day P95: ~2000m (misleading average)\n\n**If you right-size to the combined P95:**\n- Request=2400m: Over-provisioned during the day (wasting 1900m 16h/day), under-provisioned at night\n- Neither pattern is well-served\n\n## Solution: Time-Windowed Right-Sizing\n\n**Option 1: HPA with scheduled scaling**\n```yaml\napiVersion: autoscaling/v2\nkind: HorizontalPodAutoscaler\nmetadata:\n  name: bimodal-hpa\nspec:\n  minReplicas: 2   # Daytime: few replicas\n  maxReplicas: 10  # Nighttime: scale up for batch\n  metrics:\n  - type: Resource\n    resource:\n      name: cpu\n      target:\n        type: Utilization\n        averageUtilization: 70\n---\n# KEDA cron trigger for scheduled scaling\napiVersion: keda.sh/v1alpha1\nkind: ScaledObject\nspec:\n  triggers:\n  - type: cron\n    metadata:\n      timezone: America/New_York\n      start: \"0 21 * * *\"   # 9 PM: scale up\n      end: \"0 6 * * *\"      # 6 AM: scale down\n      desiredReplicas: \"8\"\n```\n\n**Option 2: Separate deployments for each mode**\n\nSplit into two deployments:\n```yaml\n# Day API service\nresources:\n  requests: {cpu: 600m, memory: 1Gi}  # Day P95 * 1.20\n  limits: {cpu: 1500m, memory: 2Gi}\nreplicas: 3\n\n# Night batch processor\nresources:\n  requests: {cpu: 4800m, memory: 4Gi}  # Night P95 * 1.20\n  limits: {cpu: 8000m, memory: 8Gi}\nreplicas: 1\n# Scaled by CronJob or KEDA\n```\n\nBenefits: Each deployment is right-sized for its pattern. No compromise.\n\n**Option 3: Time-windowed Prometheus queries**\n\n```promql\n# Daytime P95 (9 AM - 5 PM)\nquantile_over_time(0.95,\n  (rate(container_cpu_usage_seconds_total[5m]) and on() hour() >= 9 < 17)[7d:5m]\n)\n\n# Nighttime P95 (5 PM - 9 AM)  \nquantile_over_time(0.95,\n  (rate(container_cpu_usage_seconds_total[5m]) and on() (hour() >= 17 or hour() < 9))[7d:5m]\n)\n```\n\nUse daytime P95 for request sizing (scheduling), nighttime P95 for limit sizing (burst capacity).\n\n**Classification**: Tag as `pattern: bimodal` in k8s-sage metadata. This tells the recommendation engine to use time-windowed analysis, not 7-day averages.", "classification", p),
    ]


def final_expert_pairs():
    """Final pairs to reach target count."""
    p = "expert-operational-knowledge"
    return [
        make_pair("expert-edge-case-032",
            "We applied right-sizing recommendations and reduced total cluster CPU requests by 40%. The cluster autoscaler removed 5 nodes. But now during peak hours, pods are stuck Pending for 2-3 minutes while new nodes provision. How do I prevent this?",
            "## Post-Right-Sizing Node Provisioning Latency\n\n**This is the most common side-effect of aggressive right-sizing.** By reducing requests, you reduced the cluster's 'pre-provisioned' capacity. Now there's no slack for traffic spikes.\n\n**The timeline:**\n1. Before right-sizing: 15 nodes, 60% request utilisation. 40% slack = instant pod scheduling.\n2. After right-sizing: 10 nodes, 85% request utilisation. 15% slack = tight fit.\n3. Peak traffic: HPA triggers scale-up → new pods need scheduling → no node capacity → cluster autoscaler adds node → 2-3 min provisioning.\n\n## Solutions (choose one or combine)\n\n**1. Over-provisioner pods (recommended):**\nDeploy low-priority 'balloon' pods that hold capacity:\n```yaml\napiVersion: apps/v1\nkind: Deployment\nmetadata:\n  name: overprovisioner\nspec:\n  replicas: 2\n  template:\n    spec:\n      priorityClassName: overprovisioner  # Low priority\n      containers:\n      - name: pause\n        image: registry.k8s.io/pause:3.9\n        resources:\n          requests:\n            cpu: 2000m\n            memory: 4Gi\n---\napiVersion: scheduling.k8s.io/v1\nkind: PriorityClass\nmetadata:\n  name: overprovisioner\nvalue: -1  # Lowest priority\nglobalDefault: false\n```\n\nHow it works:\n- 2 pause pods each requesting 2 CPU / 4Gi = 4 CPU / 8Gi of reserved slack\n- When real pods need scheduling, the over-provisioner pods are preempted (evicted)\n- Real pods schedule instantly on the freed capacity\n- Cluster autoscaler sees evicted over-provisioner pods → provisions new node\n- Over-provisioner rescheduled on new node → slack is restored\n\n**2. Cluster autoscaler proactive scaling:**\n```\n--scale-up-from-zero=true\n--expendable-pods-priority-cutoff=-10\n--max-node-provision-time=10m\n```\n\n**3. Karpenter with capacity spread:**\n```yaml\nspec:\n  disruption:\n    consolidationPolicy: WhenEmpty  # Only remove completely empty nodes\n    # WhenUnderutilized is too aggressive post-right-sizing\n```\n\n**4. HPA with anticipatory scaling:**\n```yaml\nbehavior:\n  scaleUp:\n    stabilizationWindowSeconds: 0  # Scale up immediately\n    policies:\n    - type: Pods\n      value: 4\n      periodSeconds: 60  # Add up to 4 pods per minute\n  scaleDown:\n    stabilizationWindowSeconds: 300  # Wait 5 min before scaling down\n```\n\n**Right-sizing + capacity planning formula:**\n```\nTarget utilisation = 1 - (scale_up_time * scale_rate / total_capacity)\n```\nIf it takes 3 minutes to add a node and you need 10 pods in that time:\nSlack needed = 10 * pod_request = 10 * 500m = 5000m\nIf cluster total = 80 CPU: target utilisation = 1 - (5/80) = 93.75%\n\nKeep cluster at ≤93% request utilisation after right-sizing.", "edge-case", p),

        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-040",
            "We're running a Kubernetes version upgrade from 1.28 to 1.30. Should we expect changes in resource usage? Should we re-right-size after the upgrade?",
            "## Kubernetes Version Upgrade Resource Impact\n\n**Yes, Kubernetes version upgrades can change resource usage patterns.** Re-right-sizing after a major version upgrade is recommended.\n\n**Components affected by version upgrades:**\n\n**1. kubelet (node agent):**\n- Each version may change cgroup management, eviction thresholds, or container runtime interface\n- K8s 1.29: cgroup v2 became default. Memory accounting changed: `container_memory_working_set_bytes` may report differently\n- K8s 1.30: SidecarContainers became stable. Sidecar resource accounting changed.\n- Impact: 5-10% change in reported memory metrics\n\n**2. kube-proxy:**\n- K8s 1.29: nftables backend option. Different CPU characteristics than iptables.\n- K8s 1.31: nftables as default. kube-proxy CPU may decrease by 20-30%.\n- Impact: DaemonSet resource usage changes\n\n**3. CoreDNS:**\n- New version bundled with cluster upgrade may have different memory/CPU profile\n- DNS plugin changes can affect cache sizes\n\n**4. Container Runtime (containerd/CRI-O):**\n- Updated with node images. May change:\n  - Image pull CPU/memory\n  - Container startup overhead\n  - cgroup driver behaviour\n\n**5. Your workloads (indirect impact):**\n- Feature gates enabled by default may change behaviour:\n  - InPlacePodVerticalScaling (1.27 alpha → 1.31 beta): pods may resize without restart\n  - SidecarContainers (1.28 alpha → 1.29 beta → 1.30 stable): init container resource model changes\n  - PodReadyToStartContainersCondition: may change startup probe timing\n\n**Re-right-sizing approach after upgrade:**\n\n**Phase 1: Upgrade (week 1)**\n- Perform the upgrade\n- Keep existing resource requests (don't change anything)\n\n**Phase 2: Monitor (weeks 2-3)**\n- Compare pre-upgrade vs post-upgrade metrics:\n```promql\n# CPU change after upgrade\nrate(container_cpu_usage_seconds_total[5m])\n  - rate(container_cpu_usage_seconds_total[5m] offset 14d)\n```\n- Watch for: new OOMKills, increased throttling, changed memory patterns\n\n**Phase 3: Re-right-size (week 4)**\n- Use 2 weeks of post-upgrade metrics for new baselines\n- Re-run VPA recommendations or k8s-sage analysis\n- Apply updated requests/limits\n\n**Common post-upgrade issues:**\n1. **cgroup v2 migration**: Memory metrics change by 5-15%. container_memory_working_set_bytes may include different components.\n2. **Feature gate changes**: If you relied on alpha features that became beta/stable with different defaults.\n3. **API deprecations**: If you used deprecated API versions in VPA or HPA configs.\n4. **etcd upgrade**: Bundled etcd upgrade may change compaction behaviour, affecting etcd resource usage.", "right-sizing", p),

        make_pair("expert-edge-case-033",
            "Our staging environment uses the same container images as production but with 1/10th the traffic. Yet some pods use nearly the same amount of memory as production. Why doesn't memory scale with traffic?",
            "## Why Memory Doesn't Scale Linearly with Traffic\n\n**Memory has a large FIXED component that doesn't change with traffic.** This is one of the most important concepts for right-sizing.\n\n**Memory = Fixed + Variable**\n\n| Component | Fixed/Variable | Example |\n|-----------|---------------|--------|\n| Runtime (JVM heap, V8 engine, Go runtime) | Fixed | 200Mi-2Gi |\n| Framework (Spring, Django, Express) | Fixed | 100Mi-500Mi |\n| Libraries loaded in memory | Fixed | 50-200Mi |\n| Connection pools (DB, Redis, HTTP) | Fixed | 50-200Mi |\n| Configuration and metadata caches | Fixed | 10-100Mi |\n| In-memory caches (LRU, etc.) | Fixed (bounded) | Configured size |\n| Model weights (ML serving) | Fixed | 1-10Gi |\n| **Per-request buffers** | **Variable** | **1-100KB per request** |\n| **In-flight request state** | **Variable** | **10KB-1Mi per request** |\n\n**Example: Spring Boot microservice**\n```\nFixed:\n  JVM heap (classes, spring context): 400Mi\n  Connection pools (20 DB + 10 Redis): 100Mi\n  Micrometer metrics: 50Mi\n  JVM metaspace: 150Mi\n  Total fixed: 700Mi\n\nVariable:\n  Per-request: ~10KB * concurrent requests\n  At 1000 RPS, 100ms latency: ~100 concurrent * 10KB = 1Mi\n  At 100 RPS, 100ms latency: ~10 concurrent * 10KB = 0.1Mi\n```\n\n**Production**: 700Mi fixed + 1Mi variable = 701Mi\n**Staging (1/10 traffic)**: 700Mi fixed + 0.1Mi variable = 700.1Mi\n\n**Memory is 99.9% fixed for this service.**\n\n## Right-Sizing Implications\n\n**1. Memory right-sizing benefits from horizontal scaling, not from traffic reduction:**\n- 1 pod at 700Mi = 700Mi total\n- 2 pods at 700Mi = 1400Mi total\n- Reducing to 1 pod saves 700Mi. Reducing traffic by 90% saves 0.9Mi.\n\n**2. Staging right-sizing must be memory-aware:**\n- CPU can be 1/10th of production (CPU does scale with traffic)\n- Memory should be 60-80% of production (not 10%)\n- Setting staging memory = production/10 WILL cause OOMKills\n\n**3. For cache-dominant applications (Redis, Elasticsearch):**\n- Memory is 100% fixed (configured cache size)\n- Traffic affects CPU only\n- Staging can use the same memory as production if cache hit rate matters for testing\n\n**4. For JVM applications:**\n- Heap is fixed (-Xmx). Traffic doesn't change heap allocation.\n- Reduce heap for staging: production -Xmx=4g → staging -Xmx=1g\n- Framework overhead is still fixed. Don't go below: -Xmx=512m for Spring Boot.\n\n**Environment sizing rule of thumb:**\n```\nstaging_cpu = production_cpu * (staging_traffic / prod_traffic) * 1.5\nstaging_memory = max(production_memory * 0.5, min_runtime_memory)\n```", "edge-case", p),

        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-041",
            "We want to create a right-sizing process that runs continuously, not as a one-time exercise. What does a mature right-sizing practice look like?",
            "## Continuous Right-Sizing Maturity Model\n\n**Right-sizing is not a one-time project — it's an ongoing practice.** Resource usage changes with code deployments, traffic patterns, and infrastructure changes.\n\n### Level 1: Reactive (most organisations)\n- Someone notices high cloud bill → ad-hoc investigation\n- Manual kubectl top or single Grafana dashboard\n- Changes made directly to deployment YAMLs\n- No automation, no measurement of savings\n\n### Level 2: Periodic Review (quarterly)\n- Scheduled quarterly right-sizing review\n- VPA in recommendation-only mode\n- Dedicated Grafana dashboard for waste detection\n- Changes tracked in PRs with before/after metrics\n- Savings measured and reported to management\n\n### Level 3: Continuous Monitoring (recommended target)\n- Prometheus recording rules for waste detection (see k8s-sage rules above)\n- Automated alerts when waste exceeds thresholds:\n  - CPU request > 5x P95 usage for 7 days → alert\n  - Memory request > 3x P95 usage for 7 days → alert\n- VPA in Auto mode for non-critical workloads (Tier 3)\n- VPA in recommendation-only for critical workloads (Tier 1-2)\n- Monthly automated report: top 20 wasteful pods, savings opportunity\n- Integration with CI/CD: new deployments validated against right-sizing baselines\n\n### Level 4: Automated (advanced)\n- k8s-sage or similar tool running in-cluster\n- Automatic classification of workload patterns\n- Automated recommendations with confidence scores\n- Auto-apply for Tier 3 workloads (with rollback on performance regression)\n- Automated PR creation for Tier 1-2 workloads with human approval\n- FinOps integration: savings tracked per team, per environment\n- Cost attribution: each team sees their waste and recommendations\n\n### Implementation Steps\n\n**Week 1-2: Visibility**\n1. Deploy Prometheus + Grafana (if not already)\n2. Add recording rules for P95 CPU and memory per container\n3. Create dashboard showing waste ratio per namespace\n\n**Week 3-4: Baseline**\n4. Deploy VPA in recommendation-only mode for all workloads\n5. Document current state: total requests, total usage, waste percentage\n6. Identify top 20 wasteful workloads\n\n**Month 2: Action**\n7. Right-size top 20 workloads (PRs with metrics)\n8. Enable cluster autoscaler to consolidate freed capacity\n9. Measure savings: node count reduction, cost reduction\n\n**Month 3+: Sustain**\n10. Add CI/CD validation: block deployments with resources > 10x baseline\n11. Monthly automated waste reports\n12. Quarterly review of right-sizing policy (headroom percentages, tier definitions)\n\n**Key metrics for the practice:**\n- Cluster CPU utilisation (target: 60-80%)\n- Cluster memory utilisation (target: 70-85%)\n- Pod scheduling latency (target: <10s for 95% of pods)\n- Monthly cost trend (target: decreasing or stable despite growth)\n- Number of OOMKills per week (target: <5 across cluster)\n- CFS throttling pods (target: <10% of pods with >25% throttling)", "right-sizing", p),
    ]


# ── Batch 5: Dense pairs covering remaining topics ──────────────────

def workload_specific_batch5():
    """Workload-specific: PostgreSQL, Vector, Jaeger, oauth2-proxy, more."""
    p = "expert-operational-knowledge"
    return [
        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-042", "Workload: statefulset/postgresql\nReplicas: 3 (1 primary, 2 standby)\nContainer: postgres:16\nCPU Request: 4000m, Limit: 8000m\nMemory Request: 16Gi, Limit: 32Gi\nCPU Usage: P50=500m, P95=2000m, P99=4000m, Max=7000m\nMemory Usage: P50=12Gi, P95=13Gi, P99=13.5Gi, Max=14Gi\nPostgreSQL: shared_buffers=8Gi, work_mem=64Mi, maintenance_work_mem=512Mi, max_connections=200\nPattern: Burstable\nRestarts (7d): 0", "## Analysis\n\n**PostgreSQL memory is heavily configuration-driven, not workload-driven.** The key settings determine 90% of memory usage.\n\n**Memory breakdown:**\n- shared_buffers (8Gi): Allocated at startup, stays resident. This is PostgreSQL's primary cache.\n- Per-connection memory: ~5-10Mi per connection * 200 max = 1-2Gi at max connections\n- work_mem (64Mi): Per-sort/hash operation. Complex queries may use multiple: 64Mi * 5 ops * 10 concurrent = 3.2Gi worst case\n- maintenance_work_mem (512Mi): Used during VACUUM, CREATE INDEX\n- Total: 8Gi + 2Gi + 3.2Gi + 512Mi + overhead ≈ 14Gi (matches Max)\n\n## Recommendations\n\n**CPU**: Request=2400m (P95 * 1.20). Limit=8000m (keep, maintenance needs burst).\n- Savings: 1600m per pod = 4800m total\n\n**Memory**: Request=16.2Gi (P99 * 1.20). Limit=17.5Gi (Max * 1.25).\n- Savings: 14.5Gi limit per pod = 43.5Gi total\n\n**PostgreSQL-specific tuning:**\n1. **Reduce shared_buffers to 4Gi**: Beyond 25% of container memory has diminishing returns. PostgreSQL relies on OS page cache for double-buffering.\n2. **Reduce max_connections to 100**: Use PgBouncer for connection pooling. Each idle connection holds 5-10Mi.\n3. **Set work_mem=32Mi**: 64Mi is generous for OLTP. Prevents memory spikes from complex queries.\n4. **VACUUM tuning**: autovacuum_max_workers=3, each uses maintenance_work_mem. 3 * 512Mi = 1.5Gi during auto-vacuum.\n5. **Streaming replication**: Standby CPU is ~20-30% of primary.", "right-sizing", p, runtime="generic"),

        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-043", "Workload: daemonset/vector\nNodes: 30\nContainer: timberio/vector:0.35\nCPU Request: 500m, Limit: 2000m\nMemory Request: 512Mi, Limit: 2Gi\nCPU Usage: P50=50m, P95=200m, P99=500m, Max=1500m\nMemory Usage: P50=100Mi, P95=200Mi, P99=400Mi, Max=1Gi\nVector: collecting container logs + node metrics, shipping to Elasticsearch\nPattern: Steady with spikes during high log volume", "## Analysis\n\n**Vector is Rust-based — extremely memory-efficient.** As a DaemonSet on 30 nodes, even small over-provisioning adds up.\n\n**CPU**: Scales with log volume. P50=50m normal, Max=1500m during log storms.\n**Memory**: Rust binary (~10Mi) + configurable buffers. Max=1Gi when Elasticsearch is slow and events queue.\n\n## Recommendations\n\n**CPU**: Request=240m (P95 * 1.20). Limit=1875m (Max * 1.25).\n- Savings: 260m * 30 = 7800m total\n\n**Memory**: Request=480Mi (P99 * 1.20). Limit=1.25Gi (Max * 1.25).\n- Savings: 32Mi * 30 request = 960Mi, 750Mi * 30 limit = 22.5Gi total\n\n**Vector-specific tuning:**\n1. **Disk buffers**: Configure `buffer.type = \"disk\"` for sinks. Events spill to disk if Elasticsearch is slow. Memory stays bounded.\n2. **Rate limiting**: Add `throttle` transform to cap events/sec during log storms.\n3. **Rust memory is deterministic**: No GC, no growth. P99 is reliable for right-sizing.\n4. **Alternative to DaemonSet**: Consider sidecar deployment if only collecting container logs.", "right-sizing", p, runtime="generic"),

        make_pair("expert-edge-case-034", "Workload: deployment/jaeger-collector\nReplicas: 3\nCPU Request: 2000m, Limit: 4000m\nMemory Request: 2Gi, Limit: 4Gi\nCPU Usage: P50=300m, P95=1000m, P99=2000m, Max=3500m\nMemory Usage: P50=500Mi, P95=800Mi, P99=1.2Gi, Max=2.5Gi\nSpan ingestion: 50,000 spans/sec peak\nBackend: Elasticsearch", "## Analysis\n\n**Jaeger collector resource usage scales linearly with span ingestion rate.** The Max=2.5Gi memory spike occurs when Elasticsearch is slow — spans queue in memory.\n\n**CPU**: Each span: deserialize (~0.01ms) + index (~0.005ms) + batch for ES (~0.002ms). 50K spans/sec * 0.017ms = ~850m CPU at peak.\n\n## Recommendations\n\n**CPU**: Request=1200m (P95 * 1.20). Limit=4000m (keep).\n**Memory**: Request=1.44Gi (P99 * 1.20). Limit=3.125Gi (Max * 1.25).\n\n**Jaeger-specific tuning:**\n1. **Set `--collector.queue-size=5000`**: Limits in-memory queue. When full, new spans are dropped (tail sampling). Prevents unbounded memory growth.\n2. **Tail-based sampling**: Sample only 10% of traces. 90% less data = 90% less CPU and memory.\n3. **Kafka as buffer**: Put Kafka between collectors and Elasticsearch. Collectors write to Kafka (fast, bounded memory). Ingester reads from Kafka to ES.\n4. **Monitor `jaeger_collector_spans_dropped_total`**: Alert if spans are being dropped.", "edge-case", p, runtime="go"),

        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-044", "Workload: deployment/oauth2-proxy\nReplicas: 2\nCPU Request: 500m, Limit: 1000m\nMemory Request: 256Mi, Limit: 512Mi\nCPU Usage: P50=5m, P95=20m, P99=50m, Max=200m\nMemory Usage: P50=30Mi, P95=40Mi, P99=50Mi, Max=80Mi\nPattern: Steady", "## Analysis\n\n**oauth2-proxy is one of the simplest Go binaries.** Token validation at 1000 RPS: ~16m CPU. This is 10-25x over-provisioned.\n\n## Recommendations\n\n**CPU**: Request=24m (P95 * 1.20). Limit=250m (Max * 1.25). Savings: 476m/pod = 952m total.\n**Memory**: Request=60Mi (P99 * 1.20). Limit=100Mi. Savings: 196Mi/pod = 392Mi total.\n\n**Notes:**\n1. Despite low resources, oauth2-proxy is on the auth critical path. Keep generous limits.\n2. Use Redis for session storage for HA across replicas.\n3. Classic 'one-size-fits-all template' victim — default 500m/256Mi is 20x actual need.", "right-sizing", p, runtime="go"),

        make_pair("expert-edge-case-035", "We have a deployment that works fine with 500m CPU for weeks, then suddenly needs 4000m CPU for 2-3 hours every month. This correlates with certificate renewal. Should we size for the monthly spike or steady state?", "## Periodic Spike Workloads\n\n**Options:**\n\n**1. Size for steady state + high limit (recommended):**\n- Request=600m (steady P95 * 1.20), Limit=5000m (spike * 1.25)\n- Burstable QoS: relies on node slack during the monthly spike\n- Risk: If node is loaded during spike, CFS throttling extends renewal duration\n\n**2. Predictive HPA with KEDA:**\nUse KEDA CronScaler to scale up during the known spike window:\n```yaml\ntriggers:\n- type: cron\n  metadata:\n    start: \"0 0 1 * *\"    # First of month\n    end: \"0 3 1 * *\"      # 3 hours later\n    desiredReplicas: \"4\"   # Scale up for renewal\n```\n\n**3. Separate the heavy operation:**\nMove certificate renewal to a monthly CronJob with generous resources. Main deployment stays at 600m.\n\n**Decision framework:**\n- Spike frequency < 1/month → Option 1 (high limit, low request)\n- Spike is predictable → Option 2 (scheduled scaling)\n- Spike can be decoupled → Option 3 (separate job)\n\n**Never size the request for the monthly spike.** 600m * 720h vs 4000m * 720h: the 3400m difference is wasted for 717 of 720 hours.", "edge-case", p),

        make_pair("expert-classification-008", "How do I identify 'zombie' deployments — workloads running but no longer serving any purpose?", "## Detecting Zombie Deployments\n\n**Zombie deployments are the lowest-hanging fruit for cost savings.** They consume resources 24/7 but serve no traffic.\n\n**Detection signals:**\n\n**1. Zero network traffic (strongest signal):**\n```promql\nsum by (namespace, pod) (\n  rate(container_network_receive_bytes_total[7d])\n  + rate(container_network_transmit_bytes_total[7d])\n) == 0\n```\n\n**2. Zero CPU usage:**\n```promql\nmax_over_time(\n  rate(container_cpu_usage_seconds_total{container!=\"\"}[5m])[7d:5m]\n) < 0.001\n```\n\n**3. No recent image updates** (deployment not touched in 90+ days) combined with zero traffic.\n\n**Common zombie patterns:**\n- Feature branches deployed to staging and never cleaned up\n- A/B tests where the losing variant is still running\n- Debug deployments from incident investigations\n- Deprecated services replaced by new ones\n\n**Action plan:**\n1. Run zombie detection query weekly\n2. Label suspected zombies\n3. Notify owners (from namespace annotations or RBAC bindings)\n4. If no response in 7 days: scale to 0 (reversible, not delete)\n5. If no complaints in 30 days: delete\n\n**Expected savings:** In a typical 200-pod cluster, 10-20% of pods are zombies. Removing them frees 10-20% of cluster resources with zero functional impact.", "classification", p),

        make_pair("expert-classification-009", "Workload: deployment/cron-trigger\nReplicas: 1\nCPU Request: 500m, Limit: 1000m\nMemory Request: 256Mi, Limit: 512Mi\nCPU Usage: P50=1m, P95=1m, P99=2m, Max=50m\nMemory Usage: P50=20Mi, P95=25Mi, P99=30Mi, Max=50Mi\nThis pod runs `sleep infinity` with a sidecar that triggers CronJobs via kubectl.", "## Analysis\n\n**This is an anti-pattern.** A long-running pod that exists solely to trigger CronJobs duplicates Kubernetes's built-in CronJob functionality.\n\n**Classification: Idle (potential zombie)**\n- CPU: 500m request, 1m used = 99.8% waste\n- Memory: 256Mi request, 25Mi used = 90% waste\n\n## Recommendations\n\n**1. Replace with native CronJobs (best):**\n```yaml\napiVersion: batch/v1\nkind: CronJob\nspec:\n  schedule: \"*/5 * * * *\"\n  jobTemplate:\n    spec:\n      template:\n        spec:\n          containers:\n          - name: trigger\n            image: bitnami/kubectl:latest\n            command: [\"kubectl\", \"create\", \"job\", \"...\"]\n            resources: {requests: {cpu: 50m, memory: 32Mi}}\n          restartPolicy: Never\n      ttlSecondsAfterFinished: 60\n```\n\n**2. If keeping, minimal sizing:** Request=5m/36Mi, Limit=63m/63Mi. Saves 495m CPU.\n\n**Anti-pattern flag:** Any pod with P95 CPU < 5m + contains kubectl + purpose is scheduling → recommend conversion to native CronJob.", "classification", p),
    ]


def rightsizing_formulas_pairs():
    """Right-sizing formulas, heuristics, decision trees, management presentation."""
    p = "expert-operational-knowledge"
    return [
        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-045", "What is the complete right-sizing formula for CPU requests, CPU limits, memory requests, and memory limits?", "## Complete Right-Sizing Formula\n\n### CPU Request\n\n| Pattern | Percentile | Headroom | Formula |\n|---------|-----------|----------|--------|\n| Steady | P95 | 1.15 | P95 * 1.15 |\n| Burstable | P95 | 1.20 | P95 * 1.20 |\n| Batch | P50 | 1.50 | P50 * 1.50 |\n| Idle | - | - | 10m minimum |\n\n**Minimum**: 10m. **Data window**: 7 days minimum, 14 days preferred. **Exclude**: First 10 minutes after pod start.\n\n### CPU Limit Decision Tree\n```\nLatency-sensitive? → Consider NO limit (remove CPU limit)\nBatch/background? → Max * 1.25\nCFS throttling > 10%? → Increase limit or remove\nDefault → Max * 1.25\n```\n\n### Memory Request\n\n| Pattern | Percentile | Headroom |\n|---------|-----------|----------|\n| Steady | P95 | 1.15 |\n| Burstable | P99 | 1.20 |\n| Batch | P99 | 1.20 |\n| Idle | - | 64Mi min |\n\n**Use `container_memory_working_set_bytes`, NOT RSS.**\n**Runtime adjustments:** JVM: max(formula, heap * 1.25 + 500Mi). Python: Use Max (never releases memory).\n\n### Memory Limit\n```\nOOMKill catastrophic? (database) → Max * 1.50\nApp caches to fill memory? (ES, Redis) → configured_cache + overhead + 25%\nMemory leak risk? → Max * 1.25 (detect leaks early)\nDefault → Max * 1.25\n```\n\n### Confidence Score\n```\nconfidence = base * data_factor * stability_factor\nbase: 0.95 (14d data), 0.90 (7d), 0.80 (3d)\ndata_factor: 1.0 (no restarts), 0.8 (restarts in window)\nstability_factor: 1.0 (CV<0.5), 0.9 (CV<1.0), 0.7 (CV>1.0)\n```\nDon't auto-apply if confidence < 0.75.", "right-sizing", p),

        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-046", "I'm presenting right-sizing results to management. How do I translate pod-level metrics into dollar savings?", "## Translating Right-Sizing to Dollar Savings\n\n### Step 1: Calculate freed resources\n```promql\n# Total CPU request savings (cores)\nsum(kube_pod_container_resource_requests{resource=\"cpu\"} - (k8s_sage:container_cpu_p95:7d * 1.20)) > 0\n```\nExample: 50 CPU cores freed, 200Gi memory freed.\n\n### Step 2: Convert to nodes\n```\nnodes_freed = min(cpu_savings / allocatable_cpu_per_node, mem_savings / allocatable_mem_per_node)\n```\nWith m5.2xlarge (8 vCPU, 32Gi): CPU: 50/7.5=6.67, Memory: 200/29=6.90 → 6 nodes freed.\n\n### Step 3: Monthly savings\n6 nodes * $0.384/hr * 730h = **$1,682/month = $20,184/year**\n\n### Presentation Template\n\n| Metric | Before | After | Improvement |\n|--------|--------|-------|------------|\n| Total CPU requested | 200 cores | 150 cores | -25% |\n| Node count | 30 | 24 | -20% |\n| Monthly cost | $8,410 | $6,728 | -20% |\n| Annual savings | | | **$20,184** |\n| OOMKills/week | 12 | 2 | -83% |\n| CFS-throttled pods | 25% | 8% | -68% |\n\n### ROI\n- Engineering time: ~40 hours\n- Annual savings: $20,184\n- ROI: 505%\n- Payback period: ~8 days", "right-sizing", p),

        make_pair("expert-edge-case-036", "Workload: deployment/legacy-monolith\nReplicas: 2\nJVM: -Xmx12g -Xms12g -XX:+UseG1GC\nCPU Request: 8000m, Limit: 16000m\nMemory Request: 24Gi, Limit: 32Gi\nCPU Usage: P50=1000m, P95=3000m, P99=5000m, Max=12000m\nMemory Usage: P50=18Gi, P95=20Gi, P99=22Gi, Max=25Gi\n500K LOC Java monolith migrating to microservices. Can't change code.", "## Legacy Monolith Right-Sizing (No Code Changes)\n\n**1. JVM tuning (biggest impact):**\n```\n-Xmx8g -Xms8g             # Reduce from 12g (monitor GC)\n-XX:+UseZGC                # Lower pause times than G1GC\n-XX:MaxMetaspaceSize=512m  # Cap metaspace growth\n```\nExpected savings: 4Gi per pod = 8Gi total.\n\n**2. Container-level right-sizing:**\n- CPU: Request=3600m (P95*1.20). Limit=15000m. Savings: 4400m/pod = 8800m total.\n- Memory: Request=22Gi (with -Xmx8g: ~18Gi expected + headroom). Limit=24Gi. Savings: 8Gi/pod = 16Gi total.\n\n**3. GC monitoring:**\nAdd `-Xlog:gc*:file=/tmp/gc.log`. If GC pause stays <200ms with -Xmx8g: safe. If frequency doubles: try -Xmx10g.\n\n**4. Scheduled scaling:**\nScale from 2 to 1 replica during off-hours. Saves 50% resources for 12-16h/day.\n\n**Total savings: ~40-50% cost reduction without code changes.**", "edge-case", p, runtime="jvm"),

        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-047", "What's the impact of pod overhead (gVisor or Kata Containers) on right-sizing?", "## Container Runtime Overhead and Right-Sizing\n\n| Runtime | CPU overhead | Memory overhead |\n|---------|-------------|----------------|\n| runc (default) | ~0% | ~5-10Mi |\n| gVisor (runsc) | 2-5% | 50-100Mi |\n| Kata Containers | 5-10% | 128-256Mi |\n\n**How pod overhead affects scheduling:** Kubernetes adds `spec.overhead` to requests:\n```\neffective_request = container_requests + pod_overhead\n```\n\n**Metrics include overhead:** `container_cpu_usage_seconds_total` includes gVisor kernel CPU. P95 measurement already captures overhead.\n\n**Right-sizing adjustment:**\n- runc: Standard formulas apply\n- gVisor: Add 10% CPU headroom, 100Mi memory headroom above standard formula\n- Kata: Add 15% CPU headroom, 256Mi memory headroom\n\n**gVisor-specific patterns:**\n- Syscall-heavy workloads (high I/O): 10-20% more CPU due to userspace syscall interception\n- gVisor's netstack: 5-15% more CPU for network-heavy workloads\n- Memory overhead: sentry process uses 50-100Mi per pod", "right-sizing", p),

        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-048", "Should CPU requests and limits be the same (Guaranteed QoS) or different (Burstable QoS)?", "## Guaranteed vs Burstable QoS Decision Framework\n\n### Guaranteed (request = limit)\n**Pros:** Predictable performance, higher eviction priority, no CFS throttling surprises, required for CPU pinning.\n**Cons:** Expensive (pay for peak 100%), no burst capability.\n**Use for:** Databases, message brokers, latency-sensitive APIs (P99 <10ms SLA), stateful workloads.\n\n### Burstable (request < limit)\n**Pros:** Cost-efficient, better bin-packing, leverages idle node capacity.\n**Cons:** CFS throttling during bursts, lower eviction priority, performance depends on node load.\n**Use for:** Stateless APIs, batch jobs, internal tools, dev environments.\n\n### Recommended defaults by tier\n\n| Tier | QoS | CPU Request | Memory |\n|------|-----|------------|--------|\n| Tier 1 (revenue) | Guaranteed | P99*1.30 | P99*1.30 |\n| Tier 2 (customer) | Burstable | P95*1.20 | P99*1.20 |\n| Tier 3 (internal) | Burstable | P50*1.50 | P99*1.20 |\n| Infrastructure | Guaranteed | P95*1.20 | P99*1.20 |\n\n**Note on CPU limits:** Strong argument for removing CPU limits on Burstable workloads. CPU is compressible (throttling = slowness, not crash). Memory is incompressible (exceeding limit = OOMKill). Many teams: Burstable with memory limits but NO CPU limits.", "right-sizing", p),

        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-049", "We have 50 namespaces, each with 10-20 deployments. What's the most efficient way to right-size across the entire cluster?", "## Cluster-Wide Right-Sizing Strategy\n\n### Phase 1: Automated assessment (Day 1)\n1. Ensure Prometheus has 14 days retention\n2. Deploy kube-state-metrics\n3. Create recording rules for waste detection\n4. Deploy VPA in recommendation-only mode cluster-wide\n\n### Phase 2: Prioritised triage (Days 2-3)\n```promql\n# Top 50 most wasteful by CPU\ntopk(50, (kube_pod_container_resource_requests{resource=\"cpu\"}\n  - quantile_over_time(0.95, rate(container_cpu_usage_seconds_total[5m])[7d:5m]) * 1.20))\n```\nTypical: Top 10 workloads = 50% of waste. Top 50 = 80%.\n\n### Phase 3: Batch right-sizing (Days 4-10)\n1. **Safe batch (Day 4-5)**: >80% waste + steady pattern. Apply P95*1.20.\n2. **Moderate batch (Day 6-7)**: 50-80% waste, burstable. Apply P95*1.30 (conservative).\n3. **Careful batch (Day 8-10)**: Databases, critical APIs. Individual analysis.\n\n### Phase 4: Harvest savings (Day 11)\nEnable cluster autoscaler. Wait for node consolidation.\n\n### Phase 5: Sustain (ongoing)\nMonthly waste report. CI/CD guardrails: reject requests > 10x VPA recommendation.\n\n**Timeline for 500-workload cluster:** Assessment: 2 days. Right-sizing: 8 days. Savings realisation: 2-4 weeks. Effort: ~80 hours. Expected savings: 30-50% compute cost.", "right-sizing", p),

        make_pair("expert-edge-case-037", "We're seeing different recommendations from VPA, Goldilocks, and Prometheus queries. Which should we trust?", "## Reconciling Different Right-Sizing Recommendations\n\n**Different tools use different algorithms and time windows.**\n\n| Tool | Algorithm | Key difference |\n|------|-----------|---------------|\n| VPA | Decaying histogram | Recent data weighted MORE (exponential decay) |\n| Goldilocks | VPA recommendations | Same as VPA (it reads VPA CRD) |\n| Prometheus P95 | quantile_over_time | All data equally weighted |\n\n**VPA's decaying histogram:** Recent spike > old spike. Reactive to changes but misses periodic patterns (monthly batch).\n**Prometheus quantile_over_time:** All data equal. Captures periodic patterns but may over-recommend after one-time anomalies.\n\n**Which to trust by workload type:**\n- **Steady workloads**: VPA and Prometheus agree. Trust either.\n- **Burstable**: VPA recommends higher (conservative). Trust the higher initially.\n- **Batch**: VPA is unreliable (decay misses periodic patterns). Use Prometheus with explicit time windows.\n- **Recently changed**: VPA adapts faster. Trust VPA for new code.\n\n**Recommended approach:**\n1. Use Prometheus P95 * 1.20 as primary\n2. Compare with VPA target\n3. If VPA recommends MORE: investigate recent traffic changes\n4. If VPA recommends LESS: decay may have 'forgotten' periodic spikes\n5. Take the higher for initial change, review after 7 days", "edge-case", p),

        make_pair("expert-edge-case-038", "After right-sizing, the cluster autoscaler removed nodes. Now during peak hours, pods are Pending for 2-3 minutes while new nodes provision.", "## Post-Right-Sizing Provisioning Latency\n\n**By reducing requests, you reduced 'pre-provisioned' slack capacity.** Now traffic spikes need new nodes.\n\n**Solution 1: Over-provisioner pods (recommended):**\n```yaml\napiVersion: apps/v1\nkind: Deployment\nmetadata:\n  name: overprovisioner\nspec:\n  replicas: 2\n  template:\n    spec:\n      priorityClassName: overprovisioner  # Low priority (value: -1)\n      containers:\n      - name: pause\n        image: registry.k8s.io/pause:3.9\n        resources:\n          requests: {cpu: 2000m, memory: 4Gi}\n```\nPause pods hold capacity. When real pods need scheduling, over-provisioner is preempted instantly. Cluster autoscaler adds nodes to reschedule the over-provisioner.\n\n**Solution 2: Tune cluster autoscaler:**\n```\n--scale-down-unneeded-time=20m\n--scale-down-delay-after-add=15m\n--scale-down-utilization-threshold=0.65\n```\n\n**Solution 3: HPA with anticipatory scaling:**\n```yaml\nbehavior:\n  scaleUp:\n    stabilizationWindowSeconds: 0  # Immediate\n    policies: [{type: Pods, value: 4, periodSeconds: 60}]\n  scaleDown:\n    stabilizationWindowSeconds: 300  # Wait 5 min\n```\n\n**Capacity formula:** Target utilisation = 1 - (scale_up_time * scale_rate / total_capacity). Keep cluster at ≤93% request utilisation after right-sizing.", "edge-case", p),

        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-050", "How should I right-size init containers? Their requests affect scheduling but they only run during startup.", "## Init Container Right-Sizing\n\n**Kubernetes scheduling uses the MAXIMUM of:**\n1. Max of all init container requests (they run sequentially)\n2. Sum of all regular container requests\n\n**Example:**\n- init: db-migration (2000m CPU, 4Gi mem)\n- init: config-loader (100m, 128Mi)\n- container: app (500m, 1Gi)\n- container: sidecar (100m, 128Mi)\n\nPod effective: max(2000m, 600m) = **2000m CPU**, max(4Gi, 1.125Gi) = **4Gi memory**\n\n**The db-migration inflates scheduling footprint by 3.3x!** After startup, that capacity is wasted.\n\n## Solutions\n\n**1. Reduce init container requests:** Flyway/Liquibase migrations are mostly I/O-waiting, not CPU-bound. Reduce to 500m. New effective: max(500m, 600m) = 600m.\n\n**2. Move init work outside the pod:** Run migrations as a Helm pre-install hook or Argo CD sync wave.\n\n**3. Use native sidecar containers (K8s 1.28+):** `restartPolicy: Always` on init containers makes them sidecars. Their resources are ADDED to regular container sum, not max'd.\n\n**4. Right-size init CPU LIMITS generously:** Low request (for scheduling) + high limit (for speed). Fast init = fast rolling updates.", "right-sizing", p),

        make_pair("expert-classification-010", "How do I classify and right-size a bi-modal workload: steady during business hours (9-5) and batch processing overnight?", "## Multi-Modal Workload Classification\n\n**Standard classification fails for bi-modal workloads.** Day P95=500m (steady), Night P95=4000m (batch). Combined 7-day P95=~2000m is misleading.\n\n**Option 1: HPA with scheduled scaling (KEDA):**\n```yaml\ntriggers:\n- type: cron\n  metadata:\n    start: \"0 21 * * *\"   # 9 PM: scale up\n    end: \"0 6 * * *\"      # 6 AM: scale down\n    desiredReplicas: \"8\"\n```\n\n**Option 2: Separate deployments:**\n- Day API: requests={cpu: 600m, memory: 1Gi}, replicas=3\n- Night batch: requests={cpu: 4800m, memory: 4Gi}, replicas=1 (KEDA-scaled)\n\n**Option 3: Time-windowed Prometheus queries:**\n```promql\n# Daytime P95\nquantile_over_time(0.95,\n  (rate(container_cpu_usage_seconds_total[5m]) and on() hour() >= 9 < 17)[7d:5m])\n\n# Nighttime P95\nquantile_over_time(0.95,\n  (rate(container_cpu_usage_seconds_total[5m]) and on() (hour() >= 17 or hour() < 9))[7d:5m])\n```\nUse daytime P95 for requests, nighttime P95 for limits.\n\n**Classification**: Tag as `pattern: bimodal` in k8s-sage metadata for time-windowed analysis.", "classification", p),

        make_pair("expert-edge-case-039", "Our staging environment uses the same images as production with 1/10th traffic, yet some pods use nearly the same memory. Why doesn't memory scale with traffic?", "## Why Memory Doesn't Scale with Traffic\n\n**Memory = Fixed + Variable. For most services, fixed dominates.**\n\n| Component | Fixed/Variable |\n|-----------|---------------|\n| Runtime (JVM, V8, Go) | Fixed (200Mi-2Gi) |\n| Framework (Spring, Django) | Fixed (100-500Mi) |\n| Libraries | Fixed (50-200Mi) |\n| Connection pools | Fixed (50-200Mi) |\n| In-memory caches | Fixed (configured) |\n| Model weights (ML) | Fixed (1-10Gi) |\n| **Per-request buffers** | **Variable (~10KB/req)** |\n\n**Example: Spring Boot**\nFixed: JVM heap+context (400Mi) + pools (100Mi) + metaspace (150Mi) = 700Mi\nVariable at 1000 RPS: ~100 concurrent * 10KB = 1Mi\nVariable at 100 RPS: ~10 concurrent * 10KB = 0.1Mi\n\nProduction: 701Mi. Staging (1/10 traffic): 700.1Mi. **Memory is 99.9% fixed.**\n\n**Environment sizing rule:**\n```\nstaging_cpu = production_cpu * (staging_traffic / prod_traffic) * 1.5\nstaging_memory = max(production_memory * 0.5, min_runtime_memory)\n```\n\nDon't set staging memory = production/10 — that causes OOMKills.", "edge-case", p),

        make_pair("expert-edge-case-040", "Should I right-size workloads differently if the application has a known memory leak that the team can't fix right now?", "## Right-Sizing with Known Memory Leaks\n\n**Yes, memory leaks require a fundamentally different right-sizing approach.** Standard percentile-based sizing breaks because memory usage trends upward indefinitely.\n\n**The problem:**\n- Standard: Memory P95 is stable → set request = P95 * 1.20\n- With leak: Memory P95 grows daily → yesterday's P95 is today's P50. Any static request will eventually be exceeded.\n\n**Approach: Time-bounded right-sizing + forced restarts**\n\n**Step 1: Characterise the leak rate:**\n```promql\nrate(container_memory_working_set_bytes[24h])\n```\nExample: Grows 200Mi/day.\n\n**Step 2: Set memory limit based on acceptable restart interval:**\n```\nmemory_limit = initial_memory + (leak_rate * restart_interval) + 20% headroom\n```\n- Initial memory: 500Mi\n- Leak rate: 200Mi/day\n- Acceptable restart interval: 7 days (weekly restart)\n- Limit: 500Mi + (200Mi * 7) + 20% = 2.28Gi → set to 2.5Gi\n\n**Step 3: Configure forced restart:**\n```yaml\nlivenessProbe:\n  httpGet: {path: /health, port: 8080}\n  # OR use a custom memory check:\n  exec:\n    command: [\"sh\", \"-c\", \"test $(cat /sys/fs/cgroup/memory.current) -lt 2000000000\"]\n  periodSeconds: 60\n  failureThreshold: 1\n```\nOR use a CronJob to rolling-restart the deployment weekly:\n```bash\nkubectl rollout restart deployment/leaky-app\n```\n\n**Step 4: Monitor and alert:**\n- Alert if memory growth rate changes (leak got worse after code change)\n- Track restart frequency — if increasing, leak is accelerating\n\n**Right-sizing request:**\n- Request = initial_memory * 1.50 (covers first few hours after restart)\n- NOT based on P95 (which is inflated by the leak)\n\n**Key principle:** With leaks, right-size based on initial post-restart memory, not long-term P95. Force regular restarts to reset. This is a band-aid — fix the leak.", "edge-case", p),

        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-051", "What's the difference between right-sizing for cost vs performance? Can I optimise for both?", "## Cost vs Performance Right-Sizing\n\n**Cost-optimised:** request=P95*1.10. Accept occasional throttling during extreme peaks.\n**Performance-optimised:** request=Max*1.50. Zero tolerance for throttling. 50-70% waste.\n\n## Tier-Based Framework (both goals)\n\n**Tier 1 — Revenue-critical (5-10% of workloads):**\nPayment, auth, real-time APIs. Right-size for performance: request=P99*1.30. Guaranteed QoS. Accept 30-50% waste.\n\n**Tier 2 — Customer-facing (20-30%):**\nWeb frontends, search. Balanced: request=P95*1.20. Burstable QoS. Target 20-30% waste.\n\n**Tier 3 — Internal/batch (60-70%):**\nCI/CD, batch, dev, monitoring. Cost-optimised: request=P50*1.50, limit=P99*1.20. Accept throttling. Target <15% waste.\n\n**Result:** 40-50% cost reduction with zero performance impact on Tier 1. The 60-70% Tier 3 workloads drive most savings.\n\n**Measurement:**\nTarget utilisation: Tier 1 = 50-70%, Tier 2 = 60-80%, Tier 3 = 80-95%.", "right-sizing", p),

        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-052", "How should resource requests differ between dev, staging, and production environments?", "## Environment-Specific Right-Sizing\n\n**Production (reliability):** CPU request=P95*1.20. Memory request=P99*1.20. Replicas≥2 + HPA.\n\n**Staging (realistic testing):** CPU=Prod*0.5. Memory=Prod*0.75 (memory is less traffic-dependent). Same limits as prod (test burst behaviour). 1-2 replicas.\n\n**Development (minimum viable):** CPU request=50-100m. Memory request=minimum to boot. CPU limit=500-1000m (prevent dev workloads from starving others). 1 replica.\n\n**Savings example (10-service app):**\n\n| Env | Per-service CPU | Per-service Mem | 10 services |\n|-----|----------------|-----------------|-------------|\n| Prod | 1000m | 2Gi | 10 CPU, 20Gi |\n| Staging | 500m | 1.5Gi | 5 CPU, 15Gi |\n| Dev | 100m | 256Mi | 1 CPU, 2.5Gi |\n\n**Implementation with Kustomize overlays:**\n```\nbase/deployment.yaml       # No resources\noverlays/dev/resources.yaml # Minimal\noverlays/prod/resources.yaml # Production\n```\n\n**Key insight:** Dev environments at production sizing is the biggest waste. 50 developers * 10 services at prod resources = 500 services worth of prod capacity for development. Right-sizing dev alone saves 80-90% of dev cluster costs.", "right-sizing", p),

        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-053", "Should I right-size vertically (reduce per-pod resources) or horizontally (reduce replica count)?", "## Vertical vs Horizontal Right-Sizing\n\n| Factor | Vertical ↓ | Horizontal ↓ |\n|--------|-----------|-------------|\n| Failure domains | Keep N pods (better) | Reduce N (worse) |\n| Scheduling | Smaller pods, more options | Larger pods, fewer choices |\n| HPA granularity | More replicas to scale from | Fewer base replicas |\n| Memory overhead | N * per-process overhead | Fewer * overhead |\n\n**Choose vertical when:** Latency-sensitive (more even load distribution), services with per-process overhead, HPA is active.\n\n**Choose horizontal when:** Memory-heavy (JVM 500Mi-1Gi per instance), stateful connections (WebSocket), expensive setup per replica.\n\n**Best: Do both.**\n1. Right-size vertically first (reduce request to P95*1.20)\n2. Evaluate if N replicas is still needed\n3. If each pod handles more RPS after sizing, reduce replicas\n4. Set HPA for the new baseline\n\n**Formula:** `min_replicas = ceil(peak_rps / max_rps_per_pod) * 1.2`", "right-sizing", p),

        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-054", "How do DaemonSets differ from Deployments for right-sizing?", "## DaemonSet Right-Sizing\n\n**Key differences:**\n1. **Fixed count**: Can't reduce replicas. 50 nodes = 50 pods. Only per-pod right-sizing helps.\n2. **Node-proportional usage**: DaemonSet on 96-CPU node may use 5x more than same DaemonSet on 4-CPU node.\n3. **Impact on all nodes**: Over-provisioned DaemonSet reduces allocatable on EVERY node.\n\n**Approach:**\n- Measure across node types. Size for the LARGEST node (uniform spec).\n- Calculate total cluster impact: `per_pod_request * node_count`\n- 50 nodes * 240m = 12,000m = 12 CPUs allocated to monitoring alone.\n\n**Optimizations:**\n1. **node_exporter**: Typical 5-20m CPU, 20-40Mi memory. Default 100m/200Mi is 5-10x over-provisioned.\n2. **Guaranteed QoS**: DaemonSets should never be evicted. Set request=limit.\n3. **Separate by function**: Don't combine node_exporter + fluent-bit + falco. Different profiles and lifecycles.\n4. **GKE Autopilot**: DaemonSet pods are FREE. No right-sizing benefit.\n\n**Audit total DaemonSet overhead:**\n```promql\nsum by (daemonset) (kube_pod_container_resource_requests{resource=\"cpu\", created_by_kind=\"DaemonSet\"})\n```\nTypically 10-25% of cluster capacity. Right-sizing frees 5-15%.", "right-sizing", p),

        make_pair("expert-edge-case-041", "How do I distinguish between 'needs more memory' and 'efficiently using available memory for caching' (e.g., Elasticsearch at 95%)?", "## Cache-Aware Right-Sizing\n\n**Some applications expand to fill available memory by design.** Elasticsearch, Redis, PostgreSQL show 90-95% usage regardless of allocation. This is NOT under-provisioning.\n\n**Signals to distinguish:**\n\n**1. Configurable cache size?**\nES: `indices.fielddata.cache.size`, PostgreSQL: `shared_buffers`, Redis: `maxmemory`. If yes: memory = `cache_config + overhead + 20%`. High usage is expected.\n\n**2. Performance changes with more memory?**\nIncrease limit 8Gi→16Gi: usage rises to 15Gi but latency UNCHANGED → app is caching more but doesn't NEED it.\n\n**3. Page cache vs application memory:**\n```promql\ncontainer_memory_working_set_bytes - container_memory_rss\n```\nLarge delta = OS page cache (automatically reclaimable, not a reason to increase limits).\n\n**4. Application health indicators:**\n- ES: cache hit_rate >90% → sufficient\n- Redis: keyspace_hits/(hits+misses) >95% → sufficient\n- PostgreSQL: idx_scan/seq_scan ratio stable → shared_buffers sufficient\n\n**Decision:**\n| Indicator | Needs more | Efficiently caching |\n|-----------|-----------|--------------------|\n| OOMKills | Yes | No |\n| Performance after increase | Improves | Unchanged |\n| Cache hit rate | Low (<80%) | High (>95%) |\n\n**VPA override for cache-heavy apps:**\n```yaml\nresourcePolicy:\n  containerPolicies:\n  - containerName: elasticsearch\n    maxAllowed: {memory: 32Gi}  # Cap\n    controlledResources: [\"cpu\"]  # VPA manages CPU only\n```", "edge-case", p, runtime="generic"),

        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-055", "We applied right-sizing across the cluster. How do I build a continuous right-sizing practice?", "## Continuous Right-Sizing Maturity Model\n\n### Level 1: Reactive\nSomeone notices high cloud bill → ad-hoc investigation. Manual kubectl top.\n\n### Level 2: Periodic (quarterly)\nScheduled review. VPA in recommendation-only. Grafana dashboard. Changes tracked in PRs.\n\n### Level 3: Continuous (recommended target)\n- Prometheus recording rules for waste detection\n- Alerts: CPU request > 5x P95 for 7 days, memory request > 3x P95 for 7 days\n- VPA Auto for Tier 3, recommendation-only for Tier 1-2\n- Monthly automated waste report\n- CI/CD validation: block deployments > 10x VPA recommendation\n\n### Level 4: Automated (advanced)\n- Auto-classification of workload patterns\n- Auto-apply for Tier 3 (with rollback on regression)\n- Automated PR creation for Tier 1-2 with human approval\n- FinOps integration: savings per team, per environment\n\n### Implementation\n**Weeks 1-2**: Prometheus + Grafana + recording rules + waste dashboard\n**Weeks 3-4**: VPA recommendation-only cluster-wide. Baseline documentation.\n**Month 2**: Right-size top 20 wasteful workloads. Enable cluster autoscaler.\n**Month 3+**: CI/CD guardrails. Monthly reports. Quarterly policy review.\n\n### Key metrics\n- Cluster CPU utilisation: target 60-80%\n- Memory utilisation: target 70-85%\n- Pod scheduling latency: <10s for 95%\n- OOMKills/week: <5\n- CFS throttled pods: <10% with >25% throttling", "right-sizing", p),

        make_pair("expert-edge-case-042", "After a Kubernetes version upgrade (1.28→1.30), should we re-right-size?", "## Kubernetes Version Upgrade Resource Impact\n\n**Yes, re-right-size after major version upgrades.** Changes that affect resource usage:\n\n1. **cgroup v2** (1.29 default): Memory accounting changed. `container_memory_working_set_bytes` may report differently (5-10% variance).\n2. **SidecarContainers** (1.28→1.30 stable): Init container resource model changed. Pod effective requests may differ.\n3. **kube-proxy nftables** (1.29+): Different CPU characteristics than iptables. DaemonSet resources change.\n4. **Feature gates enabled by default**: InPlacePodVerticalScaling, PodReadyToStartContainers.\n\n**Re-right-sizing process:**\n\n**Phase 1 (week 1):** Upgrade. Keep existing resource requests.\n**Phase 2 (weeks 2-3):** Compare pre/post metrics:\n```promql\nrate(container_cpu_usage_seconds_total[5m]) - rate(container_cpu_usage_seconds_total[5m] offset 14d)\n```\nWatch for new OOMKills, increased throttling, changed memory patterns.\n**Phase 3 (week 4):** Re-run VPA or k8s-sage with 2 weeks of post-upgrade data.\n\n**Common issues:** cgroup v2 metrics change 5-15%. API deprecations in VPA/HPA configs. etcd resource changes from bundled upgrade.", "edge-case", p),
    ]


def ruby_erlang_rust_pairs() -> list[dict]:
    """Batch 6a: Ruby, Erlang/BEAM, Rust, PHP-FPM, Scala, C++, Wasm runtimes."""
    p = "https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/configuration/manage-resources-containers/"
    return [
        make_pair("expert-runtime-specific-030", "How do I right-size Ruby on Rails applications in Kubernetes?", "## Ruby/Rails Right-Sizing\n\n**Ruby's memory characteristics:**\n- MRI Ruby NEVER returns memory to the OS (like Python). RSS only grows.\n- Each Rails worker process: 200-400Mi typical, 600Mi+ for large apps.\n- Copy-on-write (CoW) with Puma: shared memory after fork degrades over time.\n\n**Sizing formula:**\n```\nmemory_request = workers * per_worker_mem + shared_overhead\n```\nExample: Puma with 4 workers, 300Mi each, 100Mi shared:\n```yaml\nresources:\n  requests: {memory: 1300Mi, cpu: 500m}\n  limits: {memory: 1600Mi}  # 20% headroom for RSS growth\n```\n\n**Key patterns:**\n1. **Memory bloat over time**: Ruby processes grow 2-3x initial size. Use `puma_worker_killer` gem to restart workers at threshold.\n2. **CPU**: Ruby has GIL — single-threaded per worker. CPU request = num_workers * 0.15 for typical web.\n3. **Jemalloc**: Replace default allocator. Reduces memory 20-30%. `LD_PRELOAD=/usr/lib/libjemalloc.so.2`.\n4. **VPA caution**: RSS-only-grows means VPA will continuously recommend increases. Set `maxAllowed` aggressively.", "runtime-specific", p, runtime="ruby"),

        make_pair("expert-runtime-specific-031", "How should I size Erlang/BEAM applications (like RabbitMQ, Elixir apps) in Kubernetes?", "## Erlang/BEAM Right-Sizing\n\n**BEAM VM is unique:**\n- Lightweight processes (millions possible, ~300 bytes each)\n- Per-process GC (no stop-the-world)\n- Scheduler threads = CPU cores by default\n\n**CPU sizing:**\nBEAM creates one scheduler per detected CPU. In K8s with CPU limits, it sees CFS quota.\n- **Problem**: BEAM on a 16-core node with 2 CPU limit creates 16 schedulers but only gets 2 cores worth of time → massive context switching.\n- **Fix**: `+S 2:2` flag or `ERL_FLAGS=\"+S 2:2\"` to match CPU limit.\n- Better: Use `+C modified` for consistent scheduling.\n\n**Memory sizing:**\n- Atom table: Fixed overhead ~1Mi, grows with module loading. NOT garbage collected.\n- Binary heap: Large binaries (>64 bytes) are reference-counted, can leak if references held.\n- ETS tables: In-memory storage, can grow unbounded.\n\n**Typical sizing:**\n```yaml\n# RabbitMQ broker\nresources:\n  requests: {memory: 2Gi, cpu: \"2\"}\n  limits: {memory: 2Gi, cpu: \"2\"}  # Guaranteed QoS critical\n```\nSet `RABBITMQ_VM_MEMORY_HIGH_WATERMARK=0.7` to leave room for non-heap.", "runtime-specific", p, runtime="erlang"),

        make_pair("expert-runtime-specific-032", "Our Rust microservices use very little memory. How should I set resource requests?", "## Rust Workload Right-Sizing\n\n**Rust characteristics:**\n- No runtime, no GC, deterministic memory\n- Typical web service: 5-20Mi RSS\n- async (tokio): one thread per core, minimal overhead\n\n**The problem with Rust in K8s:**\nMinimal resource usage means minimal requests, which means:\n1. **Burstable QoS**: First to be evicted under memory pressure\n2. **Bin-packing**: Scheduler overcommits nodes with many tiny Rust pods\n3. **Monitoring blind spots**: 10Mi usage looks like noise\n\n**Recommendations:**\n```yaml\nresources:\n  requests: {memory: 64Mi, cpu: 50m}  # Floor, not actual need\n  limits: {memory: 128Mi}  # 2x request for safety\n  # NO CPU limit — Rust benefits from burst\n```\n\n**Why floor requests matter:**\n- 50 Rust pods at 5Mi actual = 250Mi total. But 50 pods at 5Mi request = scheduler puts all 50 on one node.\n- Set requests to 64Mi minimum even if usage is 10Mi. Scheduler needs realistic signals.\n- Tokio async: CPU is spiky. Remove CPU limits, keep requests at 50-100m.\n\n**Exception**: If using `jemalloc` or custom allocators, memory can grow differently. Profile first.", "runtime-specific", p, runtime="rust"),

        make_pair("expert-runtime-specific-033", "How do I size PHP-FPM worker pools in Kubernetes?", "## PHP-FPM Right-Sizing\n\n**PHP-FPM memory model**: Fixed worker pool, each worker handles one request at a time.\n\n**Formula:**\n```\nmemory = pm.max_children * per_child_memory + 50Mi (FPM master + opcache)\ncpu = pm.max_children * avg_cpu_per_request * requests_per_second / 1000\n```\n\n**Per-child memory**: Measure with `memory_get_peak_usage(true)`. Typical: 30-80Mi for WordPress, 50-150Mi for Laravel.\n\n**Static vs Dynamic pools:**\n- `pm = static`: Predictable. Set `pm.max_children` = memory_limit / per_child. Best for K8s.\n- `pm = dynamic`: Unpredictable scaling. Memory usage varies widely. VPA struggles.\n- `pm = ondemand`: Cold starts per request. Only for very low traffic.\n\n**Example (Laravel):**\n```yaml\n# 8 workers * 100Mi + 50Mi overhead\nresources:\n  requests: {memory: 850Mi, cpu: 400m}\n  limits: {memory: 1Gi}\n```\nWith `pm.max_children = 8`, `memory_limit = 100M` in php.ini.\n\n**Key insight**: PHP DOES release memory between requests (unlike Ruby/Python). So peak != sustained. Size for peak * max_children.", "runtime-specific", p, runtime="php"),

        make_pair("expert-runtime-specific-034", "How do Scala/Akka applications differ for K8s resource sizing compared to plain Java?", "## Scala/Akka Right-Sizing\n\n**Akka adds layers on top of JVM:**\n\n1. **Actor system thread pool**: Default `fork-join-pool` with `parallelism-factor = 3.0` × available processors. With 4 CPU limit → 12 threads. With no limit on 64-core node → 192 threads = thread explosion.\n2. **Akka Cluster**: Gossip protocol uses CPU proportional to cluster size. 50-node cluster: +100-200m CPU overhead.\n3. **Akka Streams**: Backpressure buffers consume memory. Unbounded streams can OOM.\n\n**Sizing approach:**\n```yaml\nresources:\n  requests: {memory: 1Gi, cpu: \"2\"}\n  limits: {memory: 1Gi, cpu: \"2\"}  # MUST set CPU limit for thread pool\n```\nThen configure:\n```\nakka.actor.default-dispatcher.fork-join-executor {\n  parallelism-min = 2\n  parallelism-factor = 1.0\n  parallelism-max = 4  # Match CPU limit\n}\n```\n\n**Memory**: JVM heap + Akka off-heap (serialization buffers, network). Total = `-Xmx` + 30% overhead.\n**Cluster sharding**: Each shard entity = ~1KB. 100K entities = 100Mi+ for shard state alone.", "runtime-specific", p, runtime="scala"),

        make_pair("expert-runtime-specific-035", "What are the resource implications of running WebAssembly (Wasm) workloads in Kubernetes?", "## WebAssembly (Wasm) in Kubernetes\n\n**Wasm workloads via WasmEdge/Spin/wasmCloud:**\n- Startup: <1ms (vs 100ms+ for containers)\n- Memory: 1-10Mi per instance (vs 50Mi+ for minimal containers)\n- No OS layer, no runtime overhead\n\n**Sizing implications:**\n```yaml\n# Wasm pod (via runwasi or SpinKube)\nresources:\n  requests: {memory: 16Mi, cpu: 10m}\n  limits: {memory: 32Mi, cpu: 100m}\n```\n\n**Key considerations:**\n1. **Density**: 100+ Wasm instances per node vs 20-30 containers. Node-level resource pressure shifts.\n2. **Linear memory model**: Wasm memory grows page-by-page (64KB). Cannot shrink. Monitor `wasm_memory_pages` metric.\n3. **No CPU pinning**: Wasm runtime manages execution. CPU limits via CFS still apply but less meaningful.\n4. **Cold starts**: So fast that scale-to-zero is practical. Size for burst, not sustained.\n\n**Current limitations (2025):**\n- GPU access: Not yet standardized\n- Networking: WASI sockets still evolving\n- Metrics: Standard container metrics may not capture Wasm-specific behavior\n\n**Recommendation**: Set resource floors (16Mi/10m) for scheduling. Let HPA handle scaling. Wasm's value is density, not per-instance optimization.", "runtime-specific", p, runtime="wasm"),
    ]


def advanced_vpa_pairs() -> list[dict]:
    """Batch 6b: VPA algorithm internals and operational patterns."""
    p = "https://github.com/kubernetes/autoscaler/tree/master/vertical-pod-autoscaler"
    return [
        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-056", "How does the VPA recommender use exponential histograms internally?", "## VPA Histogram Internals\n\n**VPA tracks resource usage with exponential histograms, not raw percentiles.**\n\nBucket boundaries follow: `bucket[i] = firstBucket * (1 + ratio)^i`\n- CPU: firstBucket=0.01 core, ratio=0.05, ~80 buckets covering 0.01-100 cores\n- Memory: firstBucket=10MB, ratio=0.05, ~100 buckets covering 10MB-1TB\n\n**Why exponential?**\n- Fixed-width histograms waste resolution. A 1m-wide bucket is useless for a 100m pod but too coarse for a 10-core pod.\n- Exponential gives ~5% relative precision everywhere.\n\n**Sample weight decay:**\nEach sample gets weight `2^(-age/halfLife)`. Default halfLife = 24h.\n- 1-hour-old sample: weight 0.97\n- 24-hour-old sample: weight 0.50\n- 7-day-old sample: weight 0.0078\n\nThis means VPA recommendations are dominated by the last 2-3 days of data.\n\n**Percentile extraction:**\nP95 = find bucket where cumulative weight reaches 95% of total weight. Result is the bucket's upper bound (conservative).\n\n**Implication for k8s-sage**: When comparing our recommendations to VPA, expect VPA to be 5-10% higher due to bucket quantization.", "right-sizing", p),

        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-057", "VPA keeps recommending increases for my deployment. The pod never OOMs. Why?", "## VPA Recommendation Creep\n\n**Common causes:**\n\n1. **Memory-only-grows applications** (Java, Ruby, Python): RSS increases over pod lifetime. VPA sees increasing usage → recommends higher. Pod restarts → usage drops → VPA decays old data → recommends increase again.\n   - Fix: Set `maxAllowed.memory` based on actual need, not VPA suggestion.\n\n2. **Startup spike**: Application uses 2x steady-state during initialization (class loading, cache warming). VPA weights recent data but startup spike keeps appearing in rolling restarts.\n   - Fix: Use VPA `containerPolicies` with `minAllowed` set to startup requirement.\n\n3. **Periodic batch jobs**: Pod handles nightly batch processing using 3x normal resources. VPA picks up the spike.\n   - Fix: Separate batch into dedicated deployment with own VPA.\n\n4. **Decay too slow**: Default 24h half-life means a one-time spike influences recommendations for ~7 days.\n   - Fix: `--cpu-histogram-decay-half-life=12h` on recommender.\n\n**Diagnosis:**\n```bash\nkubectl describe vpa <name> | grep -A5 'Target:'\n# Compare with actual usage:\nkubectl top pod <pod> --containers\n```\nIf target >> actual P95, investigate the above causes.", "right-sizing", p),

        make_pair("expert-edge-case-043", "VPA admission controller is timing out. Pods are stuck in Pending.", "## VPA Admission Controller Timeout\n\n**Symptoms**: Pods stuck in Pending, events show `FailedCreate` with webhook timeout.\n\n**Root causes:**\n\n1. **VPA webhook unreachable**: The admission webhook pod itself is down or overloaded.\n```bash\nkubectl get pods -n kube-system -l app=vpa-admission-controller\nkubectl logs -n kube-system <vpa-admission-pod>\n```\n\n2. **Too many VPA objects**: Webhook must check all VPAs on every pod creation. 500+ VPA objects = slow lookups.\n   - Fix: Use `namespaceSelector` on webhook to limit scope.\n\n3. **Recommender not writing checkpoints**: Webhook reads from checkpoints. If recommender OOMs or is stuck, checkpoints are stale → webhook retries reading.\n```bash\nkubectl get vpa-checkpoints -A | wc -l\n```\n\n4. **Network policy blocking**: Webhook runs on port 443. Network policies may block API server → webhook traffic.\n\n**Immediate mitigation:**\n```bash\n# Set failurePolicy to Ignore (pods create without VPA mutation)\nkubectl get mutatingwebhookconfigurations vpa-webhook-config -o yaml\n# Change failurePolicy: Fail → Ignore\n```\n\n**Prevention**: Size VPA components themselves:\n- Recommender: 500m CPU, 500Mi memory (scales with VPA object count)\n- Admission controller: 200m CPU, 128Mi memory\n- Updater: 200m CPU, 256Mi memory", "edge-case", p),

        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-058", "When should I NOT use VPA?", "## When VPA Is Wrong\n\n**Do not use VPA for:**\n\n1. **HPA-scaled deployments on CPU/memory**: VPA changes requests → changes HPA's utilization percentage → HPA scales differently → VPA sees different per-pod usage → feedback loop.\n   - Exception: VPA on memory + HPA on custom metrics works fine.\n\n2. **JVM with fixed heap** (`-Xmx == -Xms`): Memory usage is constant by design. VPA recommends exactly the heap size, missing the non-heap overhead.\n   - Fix: Manual sizing = Xmx + 30% or use VPA only for CPU.\n\n3. **DaemonSets** (pre-1.30): VPA doesn't handle DaemonSets natively. Each node has different load but all pods share one VPA.\n\n4. **Pods with < 24h history**: VPA needs at least one full day cycle. Short-lived batch jobs get poor recommendations.\n\n5. **GPU workloads**: VPA doesn't manage `nvidia.com/gpu`. Only CPU and memory.\n\n6. **Workloads requiring exact resources**: Some databases (etcd, Elasticsearch) are tuned for specific memory/CPU. VPA changes break internal configuration.\n\n**Use instead:**\n- Fixed sizing + monitoring alerts for (2), (6)\n- HPA only for (1)\n- Manual sizing with k8s-sage recommendations for (3), (4)\n- Per-node configuration (DaemonSet) for (3)", "right-sizing", p),

        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-059", "How do I run VPA and HPA together safely?", "## VPA + HPA Coexistence\n\n**The core conflict**: HPA scales replicas based on `utilization = usage / request`. VPA changes request → HPA calculates different utilization → unpredictable scaling.\n\n**Safe patterns:**\n\n### Pattern 1: VPA memory + HPA custom metrics\n```yaml\napiVersion: autoscaling.k8s.io/v1\nkind: VerticalPodAutoscaler\nspec:\n  resourcePolicy:\n    containerPolicies:\n    - containerName: app\n      controlledResources: [memory]  # VPA only manages memory\n---\napiVersion: autoscaling/v2\nkind: HorizontalPodAutoscaler\nspec:\n  metrics:\n  - type: Pods\n    pods:\n      metric: {name: http_requests_per_second}\n      target: {type: AverageValue, averageValue: \"100\"}\n```\n\n### Pattern 2: VPA recommendation-only + manual apply\nVPA `updateMode: \"Off\"`. Read recommendations via API. Apply during maintenance windows. HPA operates normally between windows.\n\n### Pattern 3: Multidimensional Pod Autoscaler (MPA)\nGKE-specific. Single object manages both vertical and horizontal scaling. Not available on vanilla K8s.\n\n**Anti-pattern**: VPA Auto + HPA on CPU. This WILL oscillate. VPA increases CPU request → HPA sees lower utilization → scales down replicas → VPA sees higher per-pod usage → increases request further.", "right-sizing", p),

        make_pair("expert-classification-011", "How do I classify whether a workload should use VPA, HPA, or fixed sizing?", "## Autoscaling Strategy Classification\n\n| Workload Pattern | Strategy | Reasoning |\n|-----------------|----------|----------|\n| **Steady-state, traffic-driven** | HPA on custom metrics | Request rate varies, per-request cost is constant |\n| **Steady-state, resource-driven** | VPA Auto | Stable pattern, VPA converges quickly |\n| **Burstable, unpredictable** | HPA + VPA (memory only) | Need both horizontal and vertical flexibility |\n| **Batch/job** | Fixed sizing | Short-lived, VPA can't collect enough data |\n| **Database/stateful** | Fixed + monitoring | Databases need precise resource tuning |\n| **ML inference** | HPA on queue depth | GPU resources can't be VPA'd, scale by demand |\n| **CronJob** | Fixed, generous | Runs briefly, over-provisioning cost is minimal |\n\n**Decision tree:**\n1. Is it stateful with tuned internals (DB, cache)? → Fixed sizing\n2. Does traffic drive resource usage linearly? → HPA\n3. Is usage pattern stable but initial sizing unknown? → VPA recommendation mode → fixed\n4. Is it a long-running service with gradually changing load? → VPA Auto\n5. Does it need both more pods AND bigger pods? → HPA + VPA (memory only)\n6. Short-lived (<4h)? → Fixed sizing, measure, iterate", "classification", p),
    ]


def hpa_deep_pairs() -> list[dict]:
    """Batch 6c: HPA deep dive — stabilization, custom metrics, KEDA."""
    p = "https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/run-application/horizontal-pod-autoscale/"
    return [
        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-060", "How do I tune HPA stabilization windows to prevent flapping?", "## HPA Stabilization Window Tuning\n\n**Problem**: HPA scales up on traffic spike, scales down 5 min later, traffic returns, scales up again. Pods churning wastes resources and causes instability.\n\n**Default behavior** (since 1.23):\n- Scale-up: no stabilization (immediate)\n- Scale-down: 300s (5 min) stabilization\n\n**Tuning:**\n```yaml\nspec:\n  behavior:\n    scaleUp:\n      stabilizationWindowSeconds: 60  # Wait 60s of sustained high before scaling\n      policies:\n      - type: Percent\n        value: 100  # Max double replicas per period\n        periodSeconds: 60\n    scaleDown:\n      stabilizationWindowSeconds: 600  # 10 min cooldown\n      policies:\n      - type: Pods\n        value: 1  # Remove max 1 pod per period\n        periodSeconds: 120  # Every 2 min\n```\n\n**Guidelines by workload:**\n- **API server**: scaleDown 300-600s, scaleUp 0-30s. Fast up, slow down.\n- **Batch processor**: scaleDown 60s, scaleUp 0s. Respond quickly both ways.\n- **Database proxy**: scaleDown 900s, scaleUp 60s. Connection draining needs time.\n\n**Resource cost of stabilization**: Longer windows = more pods running after load drops = higher cost but fewer cold starts. Calculate: `extra_cost = extra_pods * per_pod_cost * avg_stabilization_duration_per_day`.", "right-sizing", p),

        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-061", "How does HPA calculate desired replicas from CPU utilization?", "## HPA Replica Calculation\n\n**Formula:**\n```\ndesiredReplicas = ceil(currentReplicas * (currentMetricValue / desiredMetricValue))\n```\n\nFor CPU utilization:\n```\ncurrentMetricValue = avg(pod_cpu_usage / pod_cpu_request) across all pods\ndesiredMetricValue = targetCPUUtilizationPercentage (e.g., 70%)\n```\n\n**Example:**\n- 3 replicas, each requesting 1 CPU\n- Current usage: 0.9, 0.8, 0.7 cores → avg utilization = 80%\n- Target: 70%\n- Desired = ceil(3 * (80/70)) = ceil(3.43) = 4 replicas\n\n**Gotchas:**\n1. **Unready pods**: Excluded from average. If 2/5 pods are starting, HPA sees 3 pods at higher utilization → scales up MORE.\n2. **Missing metrics**: Pods with no metrics assumed at 0% (scale-down) or 100% (scale-up) depending on direction. This is configurable.\n3. **Tolerance band**: HPA won't act if ratio is within 0.1 of 1.0 (i.e., 90-110% of target). Prevents micro-adjustments.\n4. **Multiple metrics**: When using multiple metrics, HPA calculates desired replicas for EACH metric and takes the MAX.\n\n**Right-sizing interaction**: If you reduce CPU request from 1000m to 500m, utilization percentage DOUBLES instantly. HPA will scale up. Always adjust HPA target when right-sizing.", "right-sizing", p),

        make_pair("expert-edge-case-044", "HPA keeps scaling to maxReplicas even though CPU usage is low. What's happening?", "## HPA Scaling to Max Despite Low CPU\n\n**Common causes:**\n\n1. **Wrong metric target**: Using `Utilization` but request is too low.\n   - Request: 50m, usage: 40m → utilization 80% → HPA scales up\n   - Fix: Right-size request first, then set HPA target.\n\n2. **Startup spike counted**: New pods use high CPU during startup (class loading, cache warming). HPA sees avg spike → scales more → more startups → more spikes.\n   - Fix: Add `scaleUp.stabilizationWindowSeconds: 120` to wait past startup.\n\n3. **Readiness probe too fast**: Pod marked ready before it finishes initializing. HPA counts it, sees high CPU.\n   - Fix: `initialDelaySeconds` on readiness probe ≥ startup duration.\n\n4. **Container resource metric vs pod metric**: `type: ContainerResource` counts only one container. Sidecar (istio-proxy) using high CPU isn't counted but affects node.\n\n5. **External metric drift**: Custom metric (queue depth) reporting incorrectly. Check:\n```bash\nkubectl get --raw /apis/custom.metrics.k8s.io/v1beta1/namespaces/default/pods/*/cpu_usage\n```\n\n**Diagnosis:**\n```bash\nkubectl describe hpa <name>\n# Look at 'Conditions' and 'Events'\n# Check 'current' vs 'target' values\n```", "edge-case", p),

        make_pair("expert-classification-012", "When should I use KEDA instead of the built-in HPA?", "## KEDA vs Native HPA\n\n**Use native HPA when:**\n- Scaling on CPU or memory utilization\n- Simple request-per-second via custom metrics adapter\n- No external event sources needed\n- Minimizing cluster dependencies\n\n**Use KEDA when:**\n- **Scale-to-zero**: Native HPA minimum is 1. KEDA scales to 0 pods and activates on demand.\n- **Queue-based scaling**: Kafka lag, RabbitMQ queue depth, SQS messages, Redis list length. KEDA has 60+ built-in scalers.\n- **Cron-based scaling**: Pre-scale before known traffic patterns.\n- **Multiple triggers**: Scale on combination of CPU + queue depth + time of day.\n- **External metrics without adapter**: KEDA bundles its own metrics adapter.\n\n**Resource implications of KEDA itself:**\n- KEDA operator: 100-200m CPU, 128-256Mi memory\n- KEDA metrics server: 100m CPU, 128Mi memory\n- Polling interval per ScaledObject: default 30s. 100 ScaledObjects = 100 metric queries per 30s.\n\n**KEDA gotcha**: Scale-to-zero means cold starts. First request after scale-to-zero waits for pod startup. Mitigate with `minReplicaCount: 1` for latency-sensitive services during business hours (use cron trigger).", "classification", p),

        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-062", "How do I size pods that are HPA-scaled to handle scale-up lag?", "## Sizing for HPA Scale-Up Lag\n\n**The problem**: HPA reacts in 15-30s + pod startup 10-60s = 25-90s before new capacity is online. During this window, existing pods must absorb the surge.\n\n**Sizing approach:**\n1. Calculate headroom per pod for burst absorption:\n```\ncpu_request = steady_state_p95 * (1 + surge_factor)\nsurge_factor = scale_up_time * traffic_ramp_rate / current_replicas\n```\n\n2. Example: 10 pods, each at 400m steady, traffic doubles in 30s, scale-up takes 45s:\n```\nsurge_factor = 45s * (10 pods * 400m / 30s) / (10 pods * 400m) = 45/30 = 1.5\ncpu_request = 400m * (1 + 1.5) = 1000m per pod\n```\nThis ensures existing 10 pods can handle 2x traffic for 45s.\n\n3. **Memory**: Must handle more concurrent requests during surge. Size for `max_concurrent * per_request_memory`.\n\n**Optimization**: Use `scaleUp.policies` with `Percent: 200` (triple replicas) instead of over-sizing each pod. Faster to add pods than to pre-allocate per-pod headroom.\n\n**Pre-scaling**: For predictable traffic (morning ramp), use KEDA cron trigger to pre-scale 15 min before expected increase.", "right-sizing", p),
    ]


def namespace_governance_pairs() -> list[dict]:
    """Batch 6d: ResourceQuota, LimitRange, governance."""
    p = "https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/policy/resource-quotas/"
    return [
        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-063", "How should I design ResourceQuotas per namespace to support right-sizing?", "## ResourceQuota Design for Right-Sizing\n\n**Anti-pattern**: Tight quotas that prevent right-sizing.\n```yaml\n# BAD: Quota exactly matches current deployment\nresources:\n  requests.cpu: \"8\"\n  requests.memory: 16Gi\n```\nProblem: Can't increase any pod's request without decreasing another.\n\n**Better approach**: Quota = current total requests + 30% headroom.\n```yaml\napiVersion: v1\nkind: ResourceQuota\nmetadata:\n  name: team-budget\nspec:\n  hard:\n    requests.cpu: \"12\"      # 8 used + 30% headroom\n    requests.memory: 24Gi   # 16Gi used + 50% headroom for memory\n    limits.cpu: \"20\"        # Allow burstable\n    limits.memory: 30Gi\n    count/deployments.apps: \"20\"  # Prevent namespace sprawl\n```\n\n**Per-priority quotas** (K8s 1.28+):\n```yaml\nscopeSelector:\n  matchExpressions:\n  - scopeName: PriorityClass\n    operator: In\n    values: [high-priority]\n```\nThis lets teams right-size within their priority tier without affecting others.\n\n**Monitoring quota utilization:**\n```promql\nkube_resourcequota{type=\"used\"} / kube_resourcequota{type=\"hard\"}\n```\nAlert at 80%. Proactively increase before teams are blocked.", "right-sizing", p),

        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-064", "How do LimitRange defaults interact with right-sizing recommendations?", "## LimitRange + Right-Sizing Interaction\n\n**LimitRange sets defaults for pods without explicit requests/limits:**\n```yaml\napiVersion: v1\nkind: LimitRange\nmetadata:\n  name: defaults\nspec:\n  limits:\n  - default:         # Default limit\n      cpu: 500m\n      memory: 512Mi\n    defaultRequest:   # Default request\n      cpu: 100m\n      memory: 128Mi\n    type: Container\n```\n\n**Impact on right-sizing:**\n\n1. **Hidden defaults**: Developer deploys pod without resources → gets 100m/128Mi from LimitRange. Pod OOMKills at 512Mi limit. Looks like under-provisioning but it's actually the LimitRange.\n   - Check: `kubectl describe pod` shows resources even when deployment YAML doesn't.\n\n2. **min/max enforcement**: LimitRange `min` and `max` override VPA recommendations.\n```yaml\nmin: {cpu: 50m, memory: 64Mi}\nmax: {cpu: \"4\", memory: 8Gi}\n```\nVPA recommends 8m CPU → clamped to 50m. k8s-sage should flag when recommendation < LimitRange min.\n\n3. **Right-sizing workflow:**\n   - Step 1: Audit LimitRange: `kubectl get limitrange -A -o yaml`\n   - Step 2: Compare VPA/k8s-sage recommendations against min/max\n   - Step 3: Adjust LimitRange OR adjust recommendation, document which\n\n**Best practice**: Set LimitRange min to absolute floor (10m CPU, 32Mi memory). Set max generous. Let right-sizing tools work within that range.", "right-sizing", p),

        make_pair("expert-edge-case-045", "Pods are Pending with 'exceeded quota' but the namespace isn't full. What's going on?", "## Quota Exceeded Despite Apparent Capacity\n\n**Common causes:**\n\n1. **Limits quota vs requests quota**: Namespace has `limits.cpu: 10` and `requests.cpu: 10`. Pod requests 100m but limits 2000m. Limits quota fills first.\n```bash\nkubectl describe resourcequota -n <ns>\n# Check both Used/Hard for requests AND limits\n```\n\n2. **Completed pods count toward quota**: Failed or Succeeded pods still consume quota until garbage collected.\n```bash\nkubectl get pods -n <ns> --field-selector=status.phase!=Running\n# Delete completed pods to free quota\n```\n\n3. **PVC count quota**: `persistentvolumeclaims: \"10\"` counts all PVCs, even unused ones.\n\n4. **Rolling update doubling**: During rolling update, old + new pods coexist. If quota = exact deployment size, rolling update fails.\n   - Fix: Quota ≥ deployment size + maxSurge.\n   - Example: 10 replicas with maxSurge=25% needs quota for 13 pods' worth.\n\n5. **Init container resources**: Init containers with high requests count against quota during pod startup, even briefly.\n\n**Quick fix:**\n```bash\n# See what's consuming quota\nkubectl get pods -n <ns> -o jsonpath='{range .items[*]}{.metadata.name}{\"\\t\"}{.spec.containers[0].resources.requests}{\"\\n\"}{end}'\n```", "edge-case", p),

        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-065", "How do I account for pod overhead in resource planning?", "## Pod Overhead Accounting\n\n**Pod overhead** (`spec.overhead`) adds to container requests/limits for scheduling but is NOT visible in container metrics.\n\n**Sources of overhead:**\n- **Kata Containers / gVisor**: Sandbox runtime overhead. Typically 50-100Mi memory, 100-200m CPU.\n- **Istio sidecar injection**: ~50Mi memory, 10-100m CPU per pod (not technically 'overhead' but adds to pod total).\n- **Ephemeral containers**: Debug containers add to pod total.\n\n**Impact on right-sizing:**\n1. **Node capacity**: Scheduler uses `sum(container_requests) + pod_overhead` for bin-packing. If overhead is 100Mi per pod and you have 50 pods per node, that's 5Gi of \"invisible\" memory.\n2. **Metrics gap**: `container_memory_working_set_bytes` shows container usage, NOT overhead. Pod-level metric includes overhead:\n```promql\n# Container-level (what VPA sees)\ncontainer_memory_working_set_bytes{container!=\"POD\"}\n# Pod-level (includes overhead)\nsum by (pod) (container_memory_working_set_bytes)\n```\n3. **Quota accounting**: ResourceQuota includes overhead in the count.\n\n**Right-sizing adjustment:**\n```\nactual_node_cost = sum(container_requests) + sum(pod_overhead) + system_reserved\nefficiency = sum(container_usage) / actual_node_cost\n```\nWith Istio: typical efficiency drops 10-15% from sidecar overhead alone.", "right-sizing", p),
    ]


def gpu_workload_pairs() -> list[dict]:
    """Batch 6e: GPU resource management in Kubernetes."""
    p = "https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/manage-gpus/scheduling-gpus/"
    return [
        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-066", "How do I right-size GPU workloads in Kubernetes?", "## GPU Right-Sizing in Kubernetes\n\n**GPU resources are fundamentally different:**\n- `nvidia.com/gpu` is an integer resource (1, 2, 4). No fractional GPUs natively.\n- GPU memory is NOT a Kubernetes resource. A pod requesting 1 GPU gets ALL memory on that GPU.\n- GPUs cannot be overcommitted (unlike CPU/memory).\n\n**Sizing strategy:**\n\n1. **GPU utilization monitoring:**\n```promql\n# nvidia-smi metrics via dcgm-exporter\nDCGM_FI_DEV_GPU_UTIL  # GPU compute utilization %\nDCGM_FI_DEV_FB_USED   # GPU memory used (bytes)\nDCGM_FI_DEV_FB_FREE   # GPU memory free (bytes)\n```\n\n2. **Right-sizing decisions:**\n   - GPU util <20% sustained → wrong GPU type or CPU-bound workload\n   - GPU memory <30% used → could use smaller GPU (A10 instead of A100)\n   - GPU util >90% → GPU is the bottleneck, adding more GPUs or upgrading\n\n3. **CPU/memory for GPU pods:**\nGPU pods need CPU for data preprocessing and memory for data loading.\n```yaml\nresources:\n  requests:\n    nvidia.com/gpu: 1\n    cpu: \"4\"        # 4:1 CPU:GPU ratio for inference\n    memory: 16Gi    # Model loading + batch buffers\n  limits:\n    nvidia.com/gpu: 1\n    memory: 20Gi\n```\n\n**Cost optimization**: GPU nodes are 10-50x more expensive. Idle GPU minutes are the biggest waste. Use KEDA to scale GPU deployments to zero when queue is empty.", "right-sizing", p),

        make_pair("expert-classification-013", "How do I detect idle or underutilized GPUs in a Kubernetes cluster?", "## GPU Idle Detection\n\n**GPU waste is extremely expensive.** A single idle A100 = ~$2/hour on cloud.\n\n**Detection metrics (via DCGM exporter):**\n```promql\n# GPU completely idle (0% utilization for 30min)\navg_over_time(DCGM_FI_DEV_GPU_UTIL[30m]) == 0\n\n# Under-utilized (< 10% for 1 hour)\navg_over_time(DCGM_FI_DEV_GPU_UTIL[1h]) < 10\n\n# Memory allocated but unused\nDCGM_FI_DEV_FB_USED / DCGM_FI_DEV_FB_TOTAL < 0.1\n```\n\n**Classification:**\n| GPU Util | Memory Used | Classification | Action |\n|----------|-------------|---------------|--------|\n| 0% | 0% | Idle | Scale to zero |\n| 0-10% | >50% | Model loaded, no traffic | Enable autoscaling |\n| 10-30% | >50% | Under-utilized | Batch requests or smaller GPU |\n| >60% | >50% | Right-sized | Monitor |\n| >90% | >80% | Saturated | Scale up or optimize |\n\n**GPU time-sharing** (MIG / MPS / GPU operator):\n- NVIDIA MIG: Partition A100 into up to 7 instances. Each gets guaranteed memory + compute.\n- NVIDIA MPS: Software sharing. Multiple pods share one GPU. Risk: one pod can starve others.\n- Use MIG for production isolation, MPS for development/notebooks.\n\n**Alert rule:**\n```yaml\n- alert: GPUIdle\n  expr: avg_over_time(DCGM_FI_DEV_GPU_UTIL[1h]) < 5\n  for: 2h\n  labels: {severity: warning}\n  annotations: {summary: \"GPU idle for 2+ hours, wasting ~$2/hr\"}\n```", "classification", p),

        make_pair("expert-edge-case-046", "A pod requests 1 GPU but the GPU OOMs even though Kubernetes shows no memory pressure. Why?", "## GPU Out-of-Memory vs Kubernetes OOM\n\n**GPU OOM and Kubernetes OOM are completely independent.**\n\nKubernetes manages: CPU, memory (system RAM), ephemeral storage.\nGPU driver manages: GPU compute, GPU memory (VRAM).\n\n**Kubernetes sees**: Pod using 2Gi system memory, well within 8Gi limit. No OOM.\n**GPU sees**: Model + activations + gradients filling 40GB VRAM on 40GB A100. CUDA OOM.\n\n**Diagnosis:**\n```bash\n# Check GPU memory (NOT kubectl top)\nnvidia-smi  # or\nkubectl exec <pod> -- nvidia-smi\n```\n\n**Common causes:**\n1. **Batch size too large**: Training batch doesn't fit in VRAM. Reduce batch size or use gradient accumulation.\n2. **Model too large for GPU**: 70B parameter model needs ~140GB in fp16. Won't fit on single A100 (80GB).\n3. **Memory fragmentation**: PyTorch caches GPU memory. `PYTORCH_CUDA_ALLOC_CONF=expandable_segments:True` helps.\n4. **Multiple processes**: Two pods sharing GPU via MPS. Combined usage exceeds VRAM.\n\n**K8s can't help**: No GPU memory requests/limits in pod spec. The GPU is a black box to K8s.\n\n**Workaround**: Use NVIDIA MIG to partition GPU memory. Or set `CUDA_VISIBLE_DEVICES` and `PYTORCH_CUDA_ALLOC_CONF` to limit per-process GPU memory.", "edge-case", p),
    ]


def debugging_methodology_pairs() -> list[dict]:
    """Batch 6f: Systematic debugging methodologies for resource issues."""
    p = "https://kubernetes.io/docs/tasks/debug/"
    return [
        make_pair("expert-edge-case-047", "Give me a systematic workflow for debugging OOMKilled pods.", "## OOMKill Debugging Workflow\n\n### Step 1: Identify WHICH OOMKill\n```bash\nkubectl describe pod <pod> | grep -A5 'Last State'\n# exitCode 137 = OOMKilled\n```\nTwo types:\n- **Container OOM**: Container exceeded its memory limit. K8s killed it.\n- **Node OOM**: Node ran out of memory. Kernel OOM killer picked a victim.\n\n### Step 2: Check limits vs usage\n```bash\nkubectl top pod <pod> --containers\nkubectl get pod <pod> -o jsonpath='{.spec.containers[*].resources}'\n```\nIf usage ≈ limit → container OOM. Increase limit.\nIf usage << limit → node OOM. Check node memory pressure.\n\n### Step 3: Check for hidden memory consumers\n```promql\n# Working set vs RSS\ncontainer_memory_working_set_bytes{pod=\"<pod>\"}\ncontainer_memory_rss{pod=\"<pod>\"}\n```\nLarge gap = page cache. Not a problem.\n\n### Step 4: Check for memory leaks\nPlot memory over time. Linear growth = leak. Sawtooth = GC (normal).\n```promql\ncontainer_memory_working_set_bytes{pod=\"<pod>\"}[24h]\n```\n\n### Step 5: Check kernel memory\n```bash\ncat /sys/fs/cgroup/memory/memory.kmem.usage_in_bytes\n```\nKernel memory (network buffers, tmpfs) counts toward limit but isn't in RSS.\n\n### Step 6: Resolution\n- Leak → fix application code\n- Legitimate growth → increase limit, add VPA\n- Kernel memory → check /dev/shm usage, reduce network buffers\n- Node OOM → right-size other pods, add nodes, check for resource hogs", "edge-case", p),

        make_pair("expert-edge-case-048", "How do I diagnose whether CFS throttling is actually affecting application performance?", "## CFS Throttling Impact Assessment\n\n**Not all throttling matters.** Some throttling is harmless background activity.\n\n### Step 1: Measure throttling\n```promql\n# Throttling percentage\nrate(container_cpu_cfs_throttled_periods_total[5m])\n/ rate(container_cpu_cfs_periods_total[5m]) * 100\n```\n<5% → negligible. 5-25% → investigate. >25% → definitely impacting.\n\n### Step 2: Correlate with latency\n```promql\n# Plot together:\nhistogram_quantile(0.99, rate(http_request_duration_seconds_bucket[5m]))\nrate(container_cpu_cfs_throttled_periods_total[5m])\n```\nIf P99 latency spikes correlate with throttling spikes → throttling is the cause.\n\n### Step 3: Identify the CFS period problem\nCFS quota is per 100ms period. A Go app with 50 goroutines can burn 500ms of CPU in 10ms wall time → throttled for remaining 90ms even with 500m limit.\n\n### Step 4: Resolution options\n1. **Increase CPU limit**: Simplest. 500m → 1000m.\n2. **Remove CPU limit entirely**: Let pod burst. Only do this if node has headroom.\n3. **Reduce parallelism**: Fewer threads/goroutines = less burst.\n4. **Use `cpuManagerPolicy: static`**: For Guaranteed QoS pods, pins to specific cores. No CFS throttling.\n\n### Step 5: Validate\nAfter change, confirm: throttling drops AND latency improves. If throttling drops but latency unchanged → throttling wasn't the cause.", "edge-case", p),

        make_pair("expert-edge-case-049", "Pods are Pending with 'Insufficient cpu' but nodes show available CPU. How do I debug?", "## Insufficient CPU Despite Available Resources\n\n**The scheduler uses REQUESTS, not actual usage.**\n\n### Step 1: Check allocatable vs allocated\n```bash\nkubectl describe node <node> | grep -A10 'Allocated resources'\n# Look at 'Requests' column, NOT 'Limits' or actual usage\n```\n\n### Step 2: Common causes\n\n**2a. Requests fully allocated:**\nNode has 4 CPUs. Pods request 3.8 CPU total. Your pod requests 500m. 3.8 + 0.5 = 4.3 > 4.0 → Pending.\nBut actual usage is 1.2 CPU. Wasted: 2.6 CPU.\n→ Right-size existing pods to free request headroom.\n\n**2b. System-reserved eating capacity:**\n```bash\nkubectl get node <node> -o jsonpath='{.status.allocatable.cpu}'\n```\n4-core node with `system-reserved=500m, kube-reserved=500m` → allocatable = 3000m.\n\n**2c. DaemonSet pods:**\nEvery node has kube-proxy (100m), flannel (100m), node-exporter (100m), fluent-bit (200m) = 500m before any workload.\n\n**2d. Pod affinity/anti-affinity:**\nPod can only schedule on specific nodes, and those are full.\n```bash\nkubectl get events --field-selector reason=FailedScheduling\n```\n\n**2e. maxPods limit:**\nNode can run max 110 pods (default). Pod count reached before CPU is full.\n\n### Step 3: Resolution\n1. Right-size over-provisioned pods (biggest impact)\n2. Add cluster autoscaler\n3. Adjust system-reserved if too generous\n4. Relax affinity constraints", "edge-case", p),

        make_pair("expert-edge-case-050", "How do I determine if a pod's memory growth is a leak or legitimate increasing usage?", "## Memory Leak vs Legitimate Growth\n\n**Key question**: Does memory grow WITHOUT a proportional increase in workload?\n\n### Pattern analysis:\n```promql\n# Memory over 24 hours\ncontainer_memory_working_set_bytes{pod=~\"myapp.*\"}[24h]\n```\n\n| Pattern | Likely Cause |\n|---------|-------------|\n| Linear growth regardless of traffic | Leak |\n| Steps aligned with traffic spikes | Legitimate caching |\n| Sawtooth (grow then drop) | GC cycles, normal |\n| Grows then plateaus | Cache filling, normal |\n| Grows, pod restarts, grows again from same point | Persistent state leak |\n| Grows, pod restarts, starts from lower baseline | In-memory leak (restarting helps) |\n\n### Correlation test:\n```promql\n# Memory per request — should be roughly constant\ncontainer_memory_working_set_bytes / rate(http_requests_total[5m])\n```\nIf memory-per-request increases over time → leak. If constant → scaling with load.\n\n### Application-level checks:\n- **JVM**: `jmap -histo` — look for growing object counts of same type\n- **Go**: `pprof` heap profile — compare two snapshots 1hr apart\n- **Python**: `tracemalloc` — snapshot comparison\n- **Node.js**: `--inspect` + Chrome DevTools heap snapshot\n\n### Action:\n- Leak confirmed → fix code, set memory limit = 2x steady state, use liveness probe to restart before OOM\n- Legitimate → increase request/limit, optionally add VPA", "edge-case", p),

        make_pair("expert-edge-case-051", "How do I detect and mitigate noisy neighbor problems in Kubernetes?", "## Noisy Neighbor Detection\n\n**Noisy neighbor**: One pod consumes disproportionate shared resources (CPU, memory bandwidth, I/O, network), degrading performance for co-located pods.\n\n### Detection:\n\n**CPU noisy neighbor:**\n```promql\n# Pod using significantly more CPU than requested\n(rate(container_cpu_usage_seconds_total[5m]) - container_spec_cpu_requests) > 1\n```\nBurstable pods exceeding requests steal CPU from others.\n\n**Memory bandwidth:**\nNot directly visible in K8s metrics. Symptoms: increased latency for ALL pods on a node during the noisy neighbor's activity.\n\n**I/O noisy neighbor:**\n```promql\nrate(container_fs_writes_bytes_total[5m]) > 100e6  # >100MB/s writes\n```\n\n### Mitigation:\n\n1. **CPU**: Set limits on burst-heavy pods. Or use `cpuManagerPolicy: static` for latency-sensitive pods (Guaranteed QoS).\n2. **Memory**: Use `memoryManagerPolicy: Static` + Topology Manager for NUMA isolation.\n3. **I/O**: Use separate storage classes with I/O limits. Or schedule I/O-heavy pods on dedicated nodes via taints.\n4. **Network**: Use bandwidth annotations (`kubernetes.io/ingress-bandwidth`, `kubernetes.io/egress-bandwidth`) with CNI support.\n\n**Nuclear option**: Taint nodes and use tolerations to physically isolate noisy workloads:\n```bash\nkubectl taint nodes <node> workload=batch:NoSchedule\n```\n\n**Cost implication**: Isolation reduces bin-packing efficiency. Quantify: `isolation_cost = dedicated_node_cost - proportional_share_cost`.", "edge-case", p),
    ]


def cost_optimization_pairs() -> list[dict]:
    """Batch 6g: Cost optimization strategies and cluster efficiency."""
    p = "https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/cluster-administration/cluster-autoscaling/"
    return [
        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-067", "How do I calculate the dollar savings from a right-sizing initiative?", "## Right-Sizing ROI Calculation\n\n**Formula:**\n```\nmonthly_savings = freed_cpu_cores * cpu_cost_per_core_month\n                + freed_memory_gb * memory_cost_per_gb_month\n```\n\n**Step 1: Measure current waste**\n```promql\n# CPU waste per namespace (cores)\nsum by (namespace) (\n  kube_pod_container_resource_requests{resource=\"cpu\"}\n  - rate(container_cpu_usage_seconds_total[24h])\n)\n\n# Memory waste per namespace (bytes)\nsum by (namespace) (\n  kube_pod_container_resource_requests{resource=\"memory\"}\n  - container_memory_working_set_bytes\n)\n```\n\n**Step 2: Cloud cost mapping**\n| Cloud | CPU/core/month | Memory/GB/month |\n|-------|---------------|----------------|\n| GKE (e2-standard) | ~$24 | ~$3.2 |\n| EKS (m5.xlarge) | ~$25 | ~$3.4 |\n| AKS (D4s_v3) | ~$23 | ~$3.1 |\n\n**Step 3: Calculate with headroom**\n```\nrecoverable_cpu = total_waste_cpu * 0.7  # Keep 30% safety margin\nrecoverable_mem = total_waste_mem * 0.6  # Memory more sensitive\nsavings = recoverable_cpu * cpu_rate + recoverable_mem * mem_rate\n```\n\n**Example**: 100-node cluster, 40% avg waste:\n- 100 nodes * 4 cores * 0.4 waste * 0.7 recoverable = 112 cores\n- 112 * $24/mo = $2,688/month CPU savings\n- Plus memory savings typically 60% of CPU savings\n- Total: ~$4,300/month = ~$51,600/year", "right-sizing", p),

        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-068", "How do I prioritize which workloads to right-size first?", "## Right-Sizing Prioritization\n\n**Framework: Impact × Ease × Risk**\n\n### Step 1: Calculate waste per workload\n```promql\n# Top 20 CPU waste (requested - used)\ntopk(20,\n  sum by (namespace, deployment) (\n    kube_pod_container_resource_requests{resource=\"cpu\"}\n    - rate(container_cpu_usage_seconds_total[7d])\n  )\n)\n```\n\n### Step 2: Score each workload\n\n| Factor | High Priority | Low Priority |\n|--------|--------------|-------------|\n| Waste amount | >4x over-provisioned | <2x over |\n| Replica count | 50+ replicas (savings multiply) | 1-2 replicas |\n| Tier | Tier 3/dev (low risk) | Tier 1/prod (high risk) |\n| Autoscaling | No HPA (static waste) | HPA active (dynamic) |\n| Owner available | Team responsive | Team unavailable |\n\n### Step 3: Execution order\n1. **Quick wins**: Dev/staging environments. Cut all requests by 50%. Minimal risk.\n2. **Big impact**: Top 10 wasteful prod workloads by dollar amount. Careful with headroom.\n3. **Systematic**: Remaining workloads namespace by namespace.\n4. **Ongoing**: VPA recommendation-only for everything, quarterly review.\n\n### Step 4: Track results\n```promql\n# Cluster-wide efficiency trend\nsum(rate(container_cpu_usage_seconds_total[1h])) / sum(kube_pod_container_resource_requests{resource=\"cpu\"})\n```\nTarget: Move from 15-25% (typical) to 50-70% (optimized).", "right-sizing", p),

        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-069", "How do I size pods for spot/preemptible node pools effectively?", "## Spot Instance Right-Sizing\n\n**Spot-specific sizing differs from on-demand:**\n\n1. **Smaller pods, more replicas**: Spot nodes can disappear with 30s notice. 20 small pods across many nodes > 4 large pods on few nodes.\n```yaml\n# On-demand: 4 replicas * 2CPU\n# Spot: 10 replicas * 800m CPU (same total, better resilience)\n```\n\n2. **Guaranteed QoS on spot = waste**: Spot nodes are for cost savings. Using Guaranteed QoS (request=limit) wastes the burst capacity you need during failover.\n```yaml\n# Good for spot:\nresources:\n  requests: {cpu: 200m, memory: 256Mi}\n  limits: {memory: 512Mi}  # No CPU limit, allow burst\n```\n\n3. **Memory sizing for graceful shutdown**: Pod gets SIGTERM, has 30s. If shutdown flushes data, need enough memory for in-flight work.\n```\nmemory = steady_state + in_flight_data_buffer\n```\n\n4. **PDB is critical**: `minAvailable: 50%` ensures spot preemption doesn't take all replicas.\n\n5. **Anti-pattern**: Stateful workloads on spot. DB replicas, Kafka brokers — rebalancing cost exceeds spot savings.\n\n**Cost comparison:**\n| Config | Monthly Cost | Availability |\n|--------|-------------|-------------|\n| 4x2CPU on-demand | $192 | 99.99% |\n| 10x800m spot | $52 | 99.5% |\n| Mix: 4 on-demand + 6 spot | $122 | 99.95% |", "right-sizing", p),

        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-070", "What's the right approach for sizing dev/staging vs production environments?", "## Environment-Specific Right-Sizing\n\n**Rule of thumb:**\n- Production: 1.0x (baseline)\n- Staging: 0.5x production resources\n- Dev: 0.25x production resources\n\n**Implementation:**\n```yaml\n# values-prod.yaml\nresources:\n  requests: {cpu: \"2\", memory: 4Gi}\n  limits: {memory: 5Gi}\n  replicas: 6\n\n# values-staging.yaml\nresources:\n  requests: {cpu: \"1\", memory: 2Gi}\n  limits: {memory: 2.5Gi}\n  replicas: 2\n\n# values-dev.yaml\nresources:\n  requests: {cpu: 250m, memory: 512Mi}\n  limits: {memory: 1Gi}\n  replicas: 1\n```\n\n**Exceptions to the ratio:**\n1. **Databases**: Staging needs enough memory for realistic query testing. If prod has 32Gi for PostgreSQL shared_buffers, staging with 2Gi will have completely different query plans. Use 0.5x minimum.\n2. **ML inference**: Model must fit in memory. 7B model needs ~14GB regardless of environment. Can't reduce.\n3. **Load testing**: Staging must temporarily scale to prod size. Use HPA or manual scale-up.\n\n**Cost impact:**\nTypical org spends 30-40% of cloud budget on non-production. Right-sizing dev/staging:\n- Dev: 75% reduction = 15% of total savings\n- Staging: 50% reduction = 10% of total savings\n- Total: 25% cloud cost reduction from non-prod alone.", "right-sizing", p),

        make_pair("expert-classification-014", "How do I classify workloads into tiers for right-sizing risk management?", "## Workload Tiering for Right-Sizing\n\n**Tier 1 — Business Critical** (conservative right-sizing)\n- Revenue-generating services, payment processing, auth\n- Approach: VPA recommendation-only, human review, change windows\n- Headroom: 40% above P99\n- Memory limit: 2x request\n- Test in staging first, monitor 48h after change\n\n**Tier 2 — Important** (moderate right-sizing)\n- Internal APIs, background processors, monitoring\n- Approach: VPA recommendation-only, automated PR, team approval\n- Headroom: 25% above P95\n- Memory limit: 1.5x request\n- Monitor 24h after change\n\n**Tier 3 — Best Effort** (aggressive right-sizing)\n- Dev environments, batch jobs, internal tools\n- Approach: VPA Auto mode or aggressive manual right-sizing\n- Headroom: 15% above P95\n- Memory limit: 1.25x request\n- Apply immediately, roll back on issues\n\n**Classification criteria:**\n| Factor | Tier 1 | Tier 2 | Tier 3 |\n|--------|--------|--------|--------|\n| User-facing | Yes | Internal | No |\n| Revenue impact | Direct | Indirect | None |\n| SLA | 99.99% | 99.9% | 99% |\n| Recovery time | Minutes matter | Hours OK | Days OK |\n\n**Label pods:**\n```yaml\nmetadata:\n  labels:\n    sage.io/tier: \"1\"  # Used by k8s-sage for risk-adjusted recommendations\n```", "classification", p),

        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-071", "How often should we run right-sizing reviews, and what triggers an ad-hoc review?", "## Right-Sizing Cadence\n\n**Scheduled reviews:**\n- **Weekly**: Automated waste report via Prometheus/Grafana. Flag workloads with >3x over-provisioning.\n- **Monthly**: Team-level review of top 10 wasteful workloads. Apply changes.\n- **Quarterly**: Full cluster efficiency audit. Update LimitRanges, quotas, defaults.\n\n**Ad-hoc triggers:**\n1. **New deployment**: Every new service gets right-sized within 2 weeks of launch (after initial data collection).\n2. **Traffic pattern change**: Product launch, seasonal shift, migration. Re-baseline after 1 week of new pattern.\n3. **Version upgrade**: New app version may have different resource profile. Monitor 48h post-deploy.\n4. **K8s upgrade**: cgroup changes, feature gate defaults. Re-baseline per cluster.\n5. **Cost spike**: Monthly bill increases >10% unexpectedly. Investigate immediately.\n6. **OOMKill cluster**: 3+ OOMKills in 24h for same workload. Under-provisioned, right-size up.\n7. **Node scaling events**: Cluster autoscaler adding nodes frequently. Check if right-sizing could avoid it.\n\n**Automation target:**\n```yaml\n# Alert: workload wasting >$50/month for >7 days\n- alert: HighWasteWorkload\n  expr: |\n    (sum by (namespace, deployment) (kube_pod_container_resource_requests{resource=\"cpu\"})\n    - sum by (namespace, deployment) (rate(container_cpu_usage_seconds_total[7d])))\n    * 24  # $/core/month approximation\n    > 50\n  for: 7d\n```", "right-sizing", p),

        make_pair("expert-edge-case-052", "We right-sized aggressively and now have cascading failures during traffic spikes. How do we recover and prevent this?", "## Recovering from Over-Aggressive Right-Sizing\n\n**Immediate recovery:**\n1. **Roll back resource changes**: `kubectl rollout undo` or apply previous values.\n2. **Scale up replicas**: Add headroom horizontally while investigating.\n3. **Remove CPU limits**: If CFS throttling is the culprit, removing limits gives immediate relief.\n\n**Root cause analysis:**\n\nCascading failure pattern: Pod A is right-sized tight → traffic spike → A gets slow → A's health check fails → A restarts → traffic shifts to Pod B → B is also tight → B fails → cascade.\n\n**Prevention framework:**\n\n1. **Never right-size request AND limit simultaneously**. Reduce request (scheduling), keep limit generous (burst capacity).\n2. **Maintain minimum headroom:**\n   - CPU request: P95 + 20% minimum\n   - Memory limit: P99 + 25% minimum\n   - Never size to P50 or average\n3. **PDB enforcement**: Always have PodDisruptionBudget with `minAvailable ≥ 50%`.\n4. **HPA buffer**: Set HPA target to 60-70%, not 80-90%. Lower target = more headroom per pod.\n5. **Circuit breakers**: Application-level protection (Envoy, Istio) to fail fast rather than cascade.\n6. **Staged rollout**: Right-size 25% of pods → observe 24h → next 25% → observe → complete.\n\n**Metrics to monitor during right-sizing rollout:**\n- P99 latency (primary indicator)\n- Error rate / 5xx rate\n- Pod restart count\n- CFS throttling percentage\n- HPA replica count changes", "edge-case", p),

        make_pair("expert-classification-015", "How do I classify whether a cluster is healthy from a resource efficiency perspective?", "## Cluster Efficiency Health Score\n\n**Key metrics and healthy ranges:**\n\n| Metric | Poor | Acceptable | Good | Excellent |\n|--------|------|-----------|------|-----------|\n| CPU utilization | <15% | 15-35% | 35-60% | 60-80% |\n| Memory utilization | <20% | 20-40% | 40-65% | 65-85% |\n| Pod density (per node) | <10 | 10-25 | 25-50 | 50+ |\n| Request accuracy (req/usage) | >5x | 3-5x | 1.5-3x | 1.2-1.5x |\n| OOMKills/week | >20 | 5-20 | 1-5 | 0 |\n| CFS throttled pods | >30% | 15-30% | 5-15% | <5% |\n\n**Composite score:**\n```\nefficiency_score = \n  0.25 * normalize(cpu_utilization, 0.6) +\n  0.25 * normalize(memory_utilization, 0.7) +\n  0.20 * normalize(1/request_ratio, 0.7) +  # Inverse: lower ratio = better\n  0.15 * normalize(1 - oomkill_rate, 1.0) +\n  0.15 * normalize(1 - throttle_rate, 1.0)\n```\n\n**Classification:**\n- 0-30: Critical inefficiency. Likely 3-5x over-provisioned.\n- 30-50: Typical. Most clusters land here pre-optimization.\n- 50-70: Well-managed. Regular right-sizing happening.\n- 70-90: Optimized. Automated right-sizing in place.\n- 90+: Aggressive. Verify not trading reliability for efficiency.\n\n**Warning**: Score >85 with OOMKills >0 = over-optimized. Efficiency without reliability is a failure.", "classification", p),

        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-072", "How do I build Prometheus recording rules for continuous right-sizing monitoring?", "## Prometheus Recording Rules for Right-Sizing\n\n**Recording rules pre-compute expensive queries for dashboards and alerts.**\n\n```yaml\ngroups:\n- name: k8s-sage-efficiency\n  interval: 5m\n  rules:\n  # CPU request vs usage ratio per deployment\n  - record: sage:deployment_cpu_request_ratio\n    expr: |\n      sum by (namespace, deployment) (\n        kube_pod_container_resource_requests{resource=\"cpu\"}\n        * on(pod) group_left(deployment)\n        label_replace(kube_pod_owner{owner_kind=\"ReplicaSet\"}, \"deployment\", \"$1\", \"owner_name\", \"(.+)-[^-]+\")\n      )\n      / sum by (namespace, deployment) (\n        rate(container_cpu_usage_seconds_total{container!=\"POD\"}[1h])\n        * on(pod) group_left(deployment)\n        label_replace(kube_pod_owner{owner_kind=\"ReplicaSet\"}, \"deployment\", \"$1\", \"owner_name\", \"(.+)-[^-]+\")\n      )\n\n  # Memory waste per namespace (GB)\n  - record: sage:namespace_memory_waste_gb\n    expr: |\n      sum by (namespace) (\n        kube_pod_container_resource_requests{resource=\"memory\"}\n        - container_memory_working_set_bytes{container!=\"POD\"}\n      ) / 1e9\n\n  # CFS throttling rate per deployment\n  - record: sage:deployment_cfs_throttle_rate\n    expr: |\n      sum by (namespace, deployment) (\n        rate(container_cpu_cfs_throttled_periods_total[5m])\n      ) / sum by (namespace, deployment) (\n        rate(container_cpu_cfs_periods_total[5m])\n      )\n\n  # Estimated monthly CPU waste cost ($24/core/month)\n  - record: sage:namespace_cpu_waste_monthly_usd\n    expr: sage:namespace_memory_waste_gb * 3.2 + (sage:deployment_cpu_request_ratio - 1) * 24\n```\n\n**Usage**: These power k8s-sage dashboards and feed into the waste detection pipeline.", "right-sizing", p),
    ]


def etcd_control_plane_pairs() -> list[dict]:
    """Batch 7a: etcd and control plane sizing."""
    p = "https://kubernetes.io/docs/setup/best-practices/"
    return [
        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-073", "How should I size etcd for a production Kubernetes cluster?", "## etcd Right-Sizing\n\n**etcd is the most resource-sensitive K8s component.** Under-sizing causes cluster-wide instability.\n\n**CPU**: etcd is latency-sensitive. High CPU contention = slow consensus = slow API server.\n- <100 nodes: 2 CPU request, 4 CPU limit\n- 100-500 nodes: 4 CPU dedicated (cpuManagerPolicy: static)\n- 500+ nodes: 8 CPU dedicated on isolated nodes\n\n**Memory**: etcd stores entire cluster state in memory.\n- Formula: `base(512Mi) + objects * avg_size`\n- 1000 pods, 500 services, 200 configmaps ≈ 1.5-2Gi\n- Large clusters (5000+ pods): 4-8Gi\n- Watch cache: additional 256Mi-1Gi depending on watch count\n\n**Disk**: Most critical. etcd WAL writes MUST be fast.\n- Required: SSD with <10ms P99 fsync latency\n- Size: 2-8Gi database (auto-compacted). WAL: 2x database.\n- Use `--quota-backend-bytes=8589934592` (8Gi) for large clusters.\n\n**Warning signs:**\n```promql\netcd_disk_wal_fsync_duration_seconds_bucket{le=\"0.01\"} # <10ms should be >99%\netcd_server_slow_apply_total  # Should be 0\netcd_server_proposals_failed_total  # Increasing = consensus issues\n```\n\n**Anti-pattern**: Running etcd on nodes shared with workloads. etcd needs dedicated I/O bandwidth.", "right-sizing", p),

        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-074", "How do I size kube-apiserver and kube-controller-manager?", "## Control Plane Sizing\n\n### kube-apiserver\n**Memory scales with**: Object count, watch count, concurrent requests.\n- <100 nodes: 1Gi request, 2Gi limit\n- 100-500 nodes: 2-4Gi request\n- 500+ nodes: 4-8Gi request\n- Per 1000 active watches: +256Mi\n\n**CPU scales with**: API request rate, webhook count, admission chains.\n- <100 nodes: 2 CPU\n- 500+ nodes: 4-8 CPU\n\n**Key flags**: `--max-requests-inflight=400 --max-mutating-requests-inflight=200` for large clusters.\n\n### kube-controller-manager\n**Memory**: Stable. 256Mi-1Gi. Spikes during large-scale operations (rolling updates across many deployments).\n**CPU**: Scales with controller count and object churn.\n- Typically 500m-2 CPU\n- `--concurrent-deployment-syncs=5` (default) — increase for large clusters\n\n### kube-scheduler\n**Memory**: 128Mi-512Mi typical. Scales with pending pod queue.\n**CPU**: Spikes during bin-packing decisions.\n- 500m-2 CPU\n- Scheduling throughput: ~100 pods/sec on 2 CPU\n\n### Managed K8s (EKS/GKE/AKS)\nControl plane is managed. You don't size it directly but:\n- EKS: control plane scales automatically, charges $0.10/hr flat\n- GKE Autopilot: fully managed\n- AKS: free control plane, but uptime SLA costs $0.10/hr", "right-sizing", p),
    ]


def advanced_patterns_pairs() -> list[dict]:
    """Batch 7b: Advanced architectural patterns for resource efficiency."""
    p = "https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/workloads/"
    return [
        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-075", "How do I handle microservices with highly variable request processing costs?", "## Variable-Cost Request Sizing\n\n**Problem**: Same endpoint, wildly different resource usage. A `/search` endpoint: simple query = 50ms/10Mi, complex aggregation = 5s/500Mi.\n\n**Approaches:**\n\n### 1. Size for P99 (safe but wasteful)\n```yaml\nresources:\n  requests: {cpu: \"2\", memory: 1Gi}  # Sized for complex queries\n```\nWaste: 90% of requests use 10% of resources.\n\n### 2. Separate into fast/slow paths\nRoute complex queries to a dedicated deployment:\n```yaml\n# Fast path: handles 90% of requests\nresources:\n  requests: {cpu: 200m, memory: 128Mi}\n  replicas: 10\n\n# Slow path: handles 10% complex queries\nresources:\n  requests: {cpu: \"2\", memory: 1Gi}\n  replicas: 3\n```\nTotal cost: (10×200m + 3×2000m) = 8 CPU vs 10×2 CPU = 20 CPU.\n\n### 3. Burstable with no CPU limit\n```yaml\nresources:\n  requests: {cpu: 200m, memory: 256Mi}  # Sized for P50\n  limits: {memory: 1Gi}  # No CPU limit, allow burst\n```\nWorks if node has headroom. Risk: noisy neighbor.\n\n### 4. Queue-based architecture\nPut complex requests on a queue. Dedicated workers auto-scale with KEDA on queue depth.\n\n**k8s-sage recommendation**: Option 2 (separate paths) gives best cost/reliability trade-off.", "right-sizing", p),

        make_pair("expert-edge-case-053", "How do init containers interact with pod resource calculations for scheduling?", "## Init Container Resource Impact\n\n**K8s scheduling rule**: Pod effective request = max(max(init_containers), sum(app_containers)).\n\n**Example:**\n```yaml\ninitContainers:\n- name: db-migrate\n  resources: {requests: {cpu: \"2\", memory: 2Gi}}\n- name: config-pull\n  resources: {requests: {cpu: 100m, memory: 64Mi}}\ncontainers:\n- name: app\n  resources: {requests: {cpu: 500m, memory: 512Mi}}\n- name: istio-proxy\n  resources: {requests: {cpu: 100m, memory: 128Mi}}\n```\n\n**Effective request:**\n- Init max: max(2 CPU/2Gi, 100m/64Mi) = 2 CPU / 2Gi\n- App sum: 500m+100m=600m CPU / 512Mi+128Mi=640Mi\n- Pod effective: max(2 CPU, 600m) = **2 CPU** / max(2Gi, 640Mi) = **2Gi**\n\nThe db-migrate init container runs for 30 seconds but forces the scheduler to find a node with 2 CPU free for the entire pod lifetime.\n\n**Impact**: Node allocatable consumed by a 500m app = 2 CPU (4x waste).\n\n**Solutions:**\n1. **Right-size init containers**: Does db-migrate really need 2 CPU? Test with 500m.\n2. **Move to a Job**: Run migrations as a separate Job, not an init container.\n3. **Sidecar containers** (K8s 1.28+): `restartPolicy: Always` on init containers. They run alongside app containers, so `sum()` is used instead of `max()`.\n4. **In-place resize** (K8s 1.30+): Resize pod after init containers complete.", "edge-case", p),

        make_pair("expert-edge-case-054", "We're seeing intermittent latency spikes that correlate with garbage collection. How should we size for GC overhead?", "## GC-Induced Latency and Right-Sizing\n\n**GC pauses cause latency spikes that look like CPU throttling but aren't.**\n\n### JVM (G1GC)\n- **Pause time**: 10-200ms typical. `-XX:MaxGCPauseMillis=100` target.\n- **CPU during GC**: G1GC uses all available cores during mixed GC. With 4 CPU limit, GC briefly uses 4 cores → other threads starved.\n- **Sizing**: CPU request should account for GC overhead: `app_cpu * 1.15` (15% GC overhead typical).\n- **Heap vs container**: `-Xmx` = 75% of container memory limit. Leave 25% for metaspace, thread stacks, native memory.\n\n### Go\n- **GC is concurrent but not free**: GOGC=100 (default) triggers at 2x live heap. Each GC uses 25% of one core.\n- **Sawtooth pattern**: Normal. Memory oscillates between 1x and 2x live set.\n- **Sizing**: memory_request = live_heap * 2.5 (accounts for GC headroom + non-heap).\n- **GOMEMLIMIT**: Set to 90% of container memory limit. Go will GC more aggressively as it approaches limit.\n\n### Node.js\n- **V8 GC**: Stop-the-world scavenges (~5ms) and mark-sweep (~50-200ms).\n- **Sizing**: `--max-old-space-size` = 80% of container memory. Leave 20% for new space + native.\n\n**Universal rule**: If P99 latency spikes correlate with GC activity (check language-specific GC logs), increase memory to reduce GC frequency rather than increasing CPU.", "edge-case", p),

        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-076", "How do I size a service mesh sidecar (Istio/Envoy) across different workload types?", "## Service Mesh Sidecar Sizing\n\n**Default Istio sidecar**: 100m CPU request, 128Mi memory request. This is often wrong.\n\n**Actual usage varies by traffic volume:**\n\n| Traffic Pattern | CPU | Memory | Notes |\n|----------------|-----|--------|-------|\n| Low (<100 RPS) | 10-30m | 40-60Mi | Over-provisioned at defaults |\n| Medium (100-1000 RPS) | 50-200m | 60-150Mi | Defaults roughly right |\n| High (>1000 RPS) | 200m-1 CPU | 150-500Mi | Defaults too low |\n| gRPC streaming | 100-500m | 100-300Mi | Higher per-connection overhead |\n| WebSocket | 50-200m | 80-200Mi per 1K connections | Connection count drives memory |\n\n**Right-sizing approach:**\n1. Deploy with defaults.\n2. After 1 week, query actual usage:\n```promql\nmax_over_time(container_cpu_usage_seconds_total{container=\"istio-proxy\"}[7d])\nmax_over_time(container_memory_working_set_bytes{container=\"istio-proxy\"}[7d])\n```\n3. Set per-workload via annotation:\n```yaml\nannotations:\n  sidecar.istio.io/proxyCPU: \"50m\"\n  sidecar.istio.io/proxyMemory: \"64Mi\"\n  sidecar.istio.io/proxyCPULimit: \"500m\"\n  sidecar.istio.io/proxyMemoryLimit: \"256Mi\"\n```\n\n**Total sidecar overhead**: With 500 pods, default sidecar = 50 CPU cores + 64Gi memory requested. Right-sizing sidecars to actual usage typically saves 60-80% of sidecar overhead.", "right-sizing", p),

        make_pair("expert-classification-016", "How do I classify whether a workload should use vertical scaling, horizontal scaling, or both?", "## Vertical vs Horizontal Scaling Decision\n\n**Decision matrix:**\n\n| Factor | Vertical (bigger pods) | Horizontal (more pods) |\n|--------|----------------------|----------------------|\n| **Stateful** | Preferred | Complex (data sharding) |\n| **Stateless** | Limited benefit | Preferred |\n| **Single-threaded** | Only option | No benefit |\n| **Memory-bound** | Preferred | Memory per pod unchanged |\n| **CPU-bound, parallelizable** | Limited | Preferred |\n| **Startup time >60s** | Preferred | Slow to react |\n| **Startup time <10s** | Either | Preferred |\n| **Cost** | Linear | Sub-linear (better) |\n| **Blast radius** | Higher (fewer big pods) | Lower (many small pods) |\n\n**Hybrid patterns:**\n\n1. **Right-size vertically, scale horizontally**: First find optimal per-pod size via VPA/k8s-sage, THEN use HPA for load.\n2. **Memory vertical, CPU horizontal**: Database with fixed memory (shared_buffers) but variable CPU (query load).\n3. **Scheduled vertical, reactive horizontal**: Increase pod size during batch windows, increase replicas for traffic spikes.\n\n**Anti-patterns:**\n- Horizontal scaling a single-threaded bottleneck (Redis without cluster)\n- Vertical scaling past node capacity (pod > node allocatable)\n- Both VPA Auto + HPA on CPU simultaneously\n\n**k8s-sage approach**: Classify workload pattern first → recommend scaling strategy → size accordingly.", "classification", p),

        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-077", "How do I account for network I/O in resource sizing?", "## Network I/O Resource Impact\n\n**Network isn't a K8s resource** but affects CPU and memory significantly.\n\n**CPU impact of networking:**\n- TLS termination: ~0.5ms CPU per request. At 10K RPS = 5 CPU cores for TLS alone.\n- Serialization (JSON/protobuf): 1-10% of total CPU depending on payload size.\n- Network policy enforcement (iptables/eBPF): 1-5% CPU overhead per pod.\n- Envoy/Istio proxy: Additional CPU proportional to request rate.\n\n**Memory impact:**\n- TCP connection buffers: ~10KB per connection (kernel). 10K connections = 100Mi.\n- Receive/send buffers: `net.core.rmem_max` * connections.\n- HTTP/2 streams: ~50KB per active stream.\n- gRPC: Connection pooling reduces memory, but each channel uses ~1Mi.\n\n**Sizing adjustments:**\n```yaml\n# High-throughput API (50K RPS, TLS, JSON)\nresources:\n  requests:\n    cpu: \"4\"     # 2 CPU app + 1 CPU TLS + 0.5 CPU serialization + 0.5 headroom\n    memory: 2Gi  # 1Gi app + 500Mi connection buffers + 500Mi headroom\n```\n\n**Monitoring:**\n```promql\n# Network bytes affecting CPU\nrate(container_network_receive_bytes_total[5m]) > 100e6  # >100MB/s = significant CPU\n```\n\n**Optimization**: Connection pooling, keep-alive, HTTP/2 multiplexing, payload compression all reduce per-request overhead.", "right-sizing", p),

        make_pair("expert-edge-case-055", "Pods keep getting evicted on one specific node but all other nodes are fine. What's happening?", "## Single-Node Eviction Debugging\n\n**Node-specific evictions indicate a local resource issue, not cluster-wide.**\n\n### Diagnosis:\n```bash\n# Check node conditions\nkubectl describe node <problem-node> | grep -A5 Conditions\n# Look for: MemoryPressure=True, DiskPressure=True, PIDPressure=True\n\n# Check eviction events\nkubectl get events --field-selector reason=Evicted,involvedObject.spec.nodeName=<node>\n```\n\n### Common causes:\n\n**1. DaemonSet eating resources on this node:**\nOne DaemonSet pod on this node is misbehaving (memory leak, stuck process) while same DaemonSet on other nodes is fine.\n```bash\nkubectl top pods --all-namespaces --field-selector spec.nodeName=<node> --sort-by=memory\n```\n\n**2. Local disk pressure:**\n- Container logs filling disk: One pod writing excessive logs.\n- Image pulls: Large images cached on this node.\n- emptyDir volumes: Pod using more than `sizeLimit`.\n```bash\ndf -h  # On the node\ndu -sh /var/lib/kubelet/pods/*/volumes/  # Per-pod volume usage\n```\n\n**3. Kernel memory leak:**\nKernel slab cache growing. `slabtop` shows unreclaimable memory. Not visible in container metrics.\n\n**4. Hardware issue:**\nBad memory DIMM causing kernel to reserve pages. Available memory shrinks over time.\n```bash\ndmesg | grep -i 'memory\\|error\\|hardware'\n```\n\n**5. Noisy neighbor without limits:**\nBurstable pod consuming all node memory. Other pods evicted by kubelet.\n\n### Fix:\nIdentify the culprit with `kubectl top` sorted by resource, cordon the node, fix or replace.", "edge-case", p),

        make_pair("expert-edge-case-056", "How do I handle right-sizing for workloads with strong weekly patterns (weekday peak, weekend low)?", "## Weekly Pattern Right-Sizing\n\n**Problem**: VPA/k8s-sage averages over time, but weekday usage is 5x weekend. Sizing for average = weekday OOMs. Sizing for peak = weekend waste.\n\n**Detection:**\n```promql\n# Weekday vs weekend ratio\navg_over_time(container_cpu_usage_seconds_total[5d:1h] offset 0d)  # Mon-Fri\n/ avg_over_time(container_cpu_usage_seconds_total[2d:1h] offset 5d)  # Sat-Sun\n```\nRatio >3 = strong weekly pattern.\n\n**Solutions:**\n\n### 1. HPA with scheduled scaling (KEDA CronTrigger)\n```yaml\ntriggers:\n- type: cron\n  metadata:\n    timezone: UTC\n    start: \"0 7 * * 1-5\"  # Mon-Fri 7am\n    end: \"0 20 * * 1-5\"   # Mon-Fri 8pm\n    desiredReplicas: \"10\"\n- type: cron\n  metadata:\n    start: \"0 0 * * 0,6\"  # Weekends\n    end: \"0 0 * * 1\"      # Monday\n    desiredReplicas: \"2\"\n```\n\n### 2. Size for weekday P95, scale down on weekends\n```yaml\nresources:\n  requests: {cpu: \"1\", memory: 1Gi}  # Weekday P95\n```\nWith HPA targeting 70% CPU — naturally scales down on weekends.\n\n### 3. VPA with day-of-week awareness (not native)\nRun VPA in Off mode. Build custom controller that applies weekday recommendations Mon-Fri and weekend recommendations Sat-Sun.\n\n**k8s-sage approach**: Classify as bi-modal pattern, report weekday and weekend recommendations separately, let operator choose strategy.", "edge-case", p),
    ]


def final_coverage_pairs() -> list[dict]:
    """Batch 8: Final pairs to reach 200 — covering remaining gaps."""
    p = "https://kubernetes.io/docs/concepts/configuration/manage-resources-containers/"
    return [
        make_pair("expert-runtime-specific-036", "How do I right-size C++ applications in Kubernetes?", "## C++ Right-Sizing\n\n**C++ gives maximum control but requires careful memory accounting.**\n\n**Memory allocator choice matters:**\n- **glibc malloc**: Default. Can fragment badly. RSS grows 2-3x actual usage due to mmap arenas (1 per thread, 64Mi each).\n  - Fix: `MALLOC_ARENA_MAX=2` in env vars.\n- **jemalloc**: Better fragmentation behavior. `LD_PRELOAD=/usr/lib/libjemalloc.so`.\n- **tcmalloc**: Google's allocator. Best for high-thread-count apps. Returns memory to OS more aggressively.\n\n**Sizing approach:**\n```yaml\nresources:\n  requests:\n    cpu: 500m    # Profile-based\n    memory: 256Mi  # Measured RSS + 30% for allocator overhead\n  limits:\n    memory: 512Mi  # 2x for fragmentation headroom\n```\n\n**Common issues:**\n1. **Thread stack memory**: Default 8Mi per thread. 100 threads = 800Mi just for stacks. Use `ulimit -s 1024` (1Mi) or `pthread_attr_setstacksize`.\n2. **Memory-mapped files**: Count toward container RSS. Large mmapped databases inflate apparent usage.\n3. **Static linking**: Larger binary, more memory per process, but no shared library overhead across pods.\n\n**Key insight**: C++ memory usage is deterministic IF you control the allocator. Profile once, right-size confidently.", "runtime-specific", p, runtime="cpp"),

        make_pair("expert-runtime-specific-037", "How do I handle Java applications that use off-heap memory (Netty, Cassandra, Spark)?", "## Java Off-Heap Right-Sizing\n\n**Off-heap memory is NOT managed by JVM GC.** It's allocated via `Unsafe.allocateMemory()` or `ByteBuffer.allocateDirect()`. It counts toward container RSS but NOT toward `-Xmx` heap.\n\n**Common off-heap consumers:**\n- **Netty**: Direct byte buffers for I/O. Each connection: 64KB-1Mi buffers.\n- **Cassandra**: Memtable off-heap, bloom filters, compression metadata. Can be 2-4x heap.\n- **Spark**: Unified memory model uses off-heap for shuffle, cache, execution.\n- **Elasticsearch**: Lucene uses mmap (counts as RSS but reclaimable).\n\n**Sizing formula:**\n```\ncontainer_memory = heap(-Xmx) + off_heap + metaspace(256Mi) + thread_stacks(threads*1Mi) + native(100Mi)\n```\n\n**Example (Cassandra):**\n```yaml\n# Heap: 8Gi, Off-heap: ~12Gi (memtable + bloom + compression)\nresources:\n  requests: {memory: 24Gi}  # 8 + 12 + 0.5 + 0.5 + 3 headroom\n  limits: {memory: 28Gi}\n```\n\n**Monitoring:**\n```promql\n# Total container memory - JVM heap ≈ off-heap + OS overhead\ncontainer_memory_working_set_bytes - jvm_memory_bytes_used{area=\"heap\"}\n```\n\n**Warning**: VPA sees total container memory, not the breakdown. It may recommend reducing memory that's actually critical off-heap allocation.", "runtime-specific", p, runtime="jvm"),

        make_pair("expert-edge-case-057", "How do I handle pods that need more resources during startup than steady state?", "## Startup Resource Spike Handling\n\n**Common in**: JVM class loading, Python model loading, Go binary startup with large init, cache warming.\n\n**The problem**: Startup needs 2-4x steady-state CPU (and sometimes memory). If you size for startup, you waste resources 99% of the time. If you size for steady state, startup is slow or fails.\n\n**Solutions:**\n\n### 1. Burstable QoS (simplest)\n```yaml\nresources:\n  requests: {cpu: 500m, memory: 1Gi}   # Steady state\n  limits: {cpu: \"2\", memory: 2Gi}       # Startup burst\n```\nRequires node headroom. Works for most workloads.\n\n### 2. Startup probe with generous resources\n```yaml\nstartupProbe:\n  httpGet: {path: /healthz, port: 8080}\n  failureThreshold: 30\n  periodSeconds: 10  # 5 min startup window\n```\nCombined with burstable QoS — pod gets full burst during startup without being killed.\n\n### 3. In-place resize (K8s 1.30+)\n```yaml\nresizePolicy:\n- resourceName: cpu\n  restartPolicy: NotRequired\n```\nStart with high CPU, controller reduces after startup completes. No pod restart needed.\n\n### 4. Init container for heavy lifting\nMove cache warming / data loading to init container. App container starts warm with lower resources.\n\n**Measurement**: Profile startup separately:\n```bash\nkubectl top pod <pod> --containers  # Run every 5s during startup\n```", "edge-case", p),

        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-078", "How should I size Prometheus and its storage for a Kubernetes cluster?", "## Prometheus Right-Sizing\n\n**Prometheus resource usage scales with time series count.**\n\n**Formula:**\n```\nmemory = active_time_series * 2KB + chunks_in_memory * avg_chunk_size\ncpu = ingestion_rate * 0.001 + query_load * 0.1\ndisk = active_series * bytes_per_sample * retention_seconds / scrape_interval\n```\n\n**Typical sizing by cluster size:**\n\n| Cluster | Series | Memory | CPU | Disk/day |\n|---------|--------|--------|-----|----------|\n| <50 nodes | 100K | 2-4Gi | 1 CPU | 2-5GB |\n| 50-200 nodes | 500K | 8-16Gi | 2-4 CPU | 10-30GB |\n| 200-1000 nodes | 2M+ | 32-64Gi | 4-8 CPU | 50-150GB |\n\n**Key insights:**\n1. **Cardinality is king**: One bad metric with high-cardinality label can double memory. Monitor `prometheus_tsdb_head_series`.\n2. **Query memory**: Complex queries (large range, many series) can spike memory 3-5x baseline. Set `--query.max-samples=50000000`.\n3. **WAL**: Write-ahead log grows during spikes. Reserve 3x typical WAL size.\n4. **Remote write**: Adds 30-50% CPU and memory overhead for each remote write target.\n\n**Right-sizing steps:**\n```promql\n# Current series count\nprometheus_tsdb_head_series\n# Ingestion rate\nrate(prometheus_tsdb_head_samples_appended_total[5m])\n# Memory for series\nprometheus_tsdb_head_series * 2048  # ~2KB per series\n```", "right-sizing", p),

        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-079", "How do I size Redis for different usage patterns in Kubernetes?", "## Redis Right-Sizing by Pattern\n\n**Redis is single-threaded for commands.** CPU limit >1 doesn't help (but >1 is needed for background tasks).\n\n### Pattern 1: Cache (most common)\n```yaml\nresources:\n  requests: {cpu: 500m, memory: 2Gi}\n  limits: {cpu: \"1\", memory: 2Gi}  # Guaranteed QoS for cache\n```\nSet `maxmemory = 1.5Gi` (75% of limit). Eviction policy: `allkeys-lru`.\nUsage will always be ~maxmemory. This is CORRECT, not over-provisioned.\n\n### Pattern 2: Session store\nSmaller, more connections.\n```yaml\nresources:\n  requests: {cpu: 200m, memory: 512Mi}\n  limits: {memory: 512Mi}\n```\nSession size * max_sessions + 20% overhead.\n\n### Pattern 3: Message broker (pub/sub, streams)\nCPU-heavier, memory for pending messages.\n```yaml\nresources:\n  requests: {cpu: \"1\", memory: 4Gi}\n  limits: {memory: 4Gi}\n```\n\n### Pattern 4: Sorted sets / leaderboards\nMemory scales with cardinality.\n```\nmemory = entries * (key_size + 16 bytes overhead per entry)\n```\n1M entries with 100-byte keys ≈ 120Mi.\n\n**Common mistake**: VPA recommends reducing Redis memory because it sees steady 1.5Gi usage on a 2Gi limit. But 1.5Gi IS the maxmemory working as intended. Override VPA for Redis:\n```yaml\nresourcePolicy:\n  containerPolicies:\n  - containerName: redis\n    controlledResources: [cpu]  # VPA manages CPU only\n```", "right-sizing", p),

        make_pair("expert-classification-017", "How do I classify whether a workload is CPU-bound, memory-bound, I/O-bound, or network-bound?", "## Workload Bottleneck Classification\n\n**Identify the bottleneck before right-sizing.** Increasing the wrong resource wastes money.\n\n### CPU-bound signals:\n```promql\nrate(container_cpu_usage_seconds_total[5m]) / container_spec_cpu_quota * container_spec_cpu_period > 0.8\nrate(container_cpu_cfs_throttled_periods_total[5m]) / rate(container_cpu_cfs_periods_total[5m]) > 0.1\n```\n- High CPU utilization AND high throttling\n- Latency improves with more CPU\n- Load average > CPU count\n\n### Memory-bound signals:\n- OOMKills or OOM events\n- Working set > 80% of limit\n- Application GC frequency increasing\n- Swap usage (if enabled)\n\n### I/O-bound signals:\n```promql\nrate(container_fs_reads_seconds_total[5m]) + rate(container_fs_writes_seconds_total[5m]) > 0.5\n```\n- High I/O wait (`iowait` in node metrics)\n- Low CPU utilization despite slow response\n- Latency correlates with disk operations\n\n### Network-bound signals:\n- Low CPU, low memory, but high latency\n- Latency increases linearly with payload size\n- Connection count near limit\n\n**Classification action:**\n| Bottleneck | Right-sizing action |\n|-----------|--------------------|\n| CPU | Increase CPU request/limit or remove limit |\n| Memory | Increase memory request AND limit |\n| I/O | Move to faster storage class, not more CPU/memory |\n| Network | Optimize payloads, connection pooling. Resources won't help |", "classification", p),

        make_pair("expert-edge-case-058", "tmpfs and emptyDir volumes are causing OOMKills. How do I account for them?", "## tmpfs / emptyDir Memory Accounting\n\n**Critical**: `emptyDir` with `medium: Memory` uses tmpfs, which counts against the container's memory limit in cgroup v2.\n\n```yaml\nvolumes:\n- name: cache\n  emptyDir:\n    medium: Memory\n    sizeLimit: 500Mi\n```\n\nThis 500Mi comes FROM the container's memory cgroup. If container limit is 1Gi:\n- Available for application: 1Gi - 500Mi = 500Mi\n- Write 600Mi to tmpfs → OOMKill (total cgroup usage > 1Gi)\n\n**Diagnosis:**\n```bash\n# Check tmpfs usage inside pod\ndf -h /dev/shm  # or the mounted path\ndu -sh /path/to/emptydir\n```\n\n```promql\n# Container memory includes tmpfs\ncontainer_memory_working_set_bytes  # Includes tmpfs in cgroup v2\ncontainer_memory_rss               # Does NOT include tmpfs\n# Difference ≈ page cache + tmpfs\n```\n\n**Sizing formula:**\n```\nmemory_limit = app_memory + tmpfs_sizeLimit + 15% headroom\n```\n\n**Solutions:**\n1. **Increase memory limit** to cover tmpfs usage.\n2. **Use disk-backed emptyDir** (remove `medium: Memory`). Slower but doesn't affect memory limit.\n3. **Set sizeLimit on emptyDir**: Without sizeLimit, tmpfs can grow to 50% of node memory.\n4. **Monitor**: Alert when tmpfs usage > 80% of sizeLimit.\n\n**VPA blind spot**: VPA sees total memory including tmpfs but doesn't know about the tmpfs allocation. It may recommend a memory limit that leaves insufficient room for tmpfs.", "edge-case", p),

        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-080", "How do I calculate the total cluster cost of over-provisioning DaemonSets?", "## DaemonSet Over-Provisioning Cost\n\n**DaemonSets multiply waste by node count.** A 200m CPU over-provision on one DaemonSet across 100 nodes = 20 CPU cores wasted.\n\n**Audit query:**\n```promql\n# CPU waste per DaemonSet across cluster\nsum by (daemonset) (\n  kube_pod_container_resource_requests{resource=\"cpu\", created_by_kind=\"DaemonSet\"}\n  - on(pod,container) rate(container_cpu_usage_seconds_total{container!=\"POD\"}[1h])\n) * on() group_left() count(kube_node_info)\n```\n\n**Typical DaemonSet waste (100-node cluster):**\n\n| DaemonSet | Default Request | Actual P95 | Waste/Node | Cluster Waste |\n|-----------|----------------|-----------|-----------|---------------|\n| kube-proxy | 100m | 10m | 90m | 9 CPU |\n| fluent-bit | 200m/256Mi | 50m/80Mi | 150m/176Mi | 15 CPU / 17Gi |\n| node-exporter | 100m/200Mi | 5m/20Mi | 95m/180Mi | 9.5 CPU / 17.5Gi |\n| datadog-agent | 200m/256Mi | 80m/150Mi | 120m/106Mi | 12 CPU / 10Gi |\n| **Total** | | | | **45.5 CPU / 44.5Gi** |\n\n**Cost at $24/core/mo + $3.2/Gi/mo:**\n- CPU: 45.5 × $24 = $1,092/month\n- Memory: 44.5 × $3.2 = $142/month\n- **Total DaemonSet waste: $1,234/month = $14,808/year**\n\n**Action**: Right-size the top 4 DaemonSets. Typical savings: 60-80% of waste = $9,000-12,000/year.\n\n**Command to find DaemonSet resource requests:**\n```bash\nkubectl get ds -A -o jsonpath='{range .items[*]}{.metadata.namespace}/{.metadata.name}: cpu={.spec.template.spec.containers[0].resources.requests.cpu} mem={.spec.template.spec.containers[0].resources.requests.memory}{\"\\n\"}{end}'\n```", "right-sizing", p),

        make_pair("expert-right-sizing-081", "How do I size CoreDNS for large Kubernetes clusters?", "## CoreDNS Right-Sizing\n\n**CoreDNS scales with DNS query rate, which scales with pod count and service count.**\n\n**Default**: 100m CPU, 70Mi memory. Fine for <500 pods.\n\n**Scaling formula:**\n```\nreplicas = max(2, ceil(pods / 256))  # K8s recommendation\ncpu_per_replica = 100m + (queries_per_second / 10000) * 100m\nmemory_per_replica = 70Mi + (service_count / 1000) * 30Mi\n```\n\n**Sizing by cluster size:**\n\n| Pods | Services | QPS | Replicas | CPU/replica | Memory/replica |\n|------|----------|-----|----------|-------------|---------------|\n| 500 | 100 | 5K | 2 | 150m | 80Mi |\n| 2000 | 500 | 20K | 8 | 300m | 85Mi |\n| 5000 | 1000 | 50K | 20 | 600m | 100Mi |\n\n**Common issues:**\n1. **ndots:5 default**: Every DNS lookup tries 5 suffixes before external. Generates 5x more queries. Set `ndots: 2` in pod dnsConfig or use FQDN (trailing dot).\n2. **NodeLocal DNSCache**: Reduces CoreDNS load 80-90%. Each node runs a DNS cache. CoreDNS only handles cache misses.\n3. **Autopath plugin**: Reduces lookup chain but increases CoreDNS memory.\n\n**Monitoring:**\n```promql\ncoredns_dns_requests_total  # Total QPS\ncoredns_dns_responses_total{rcode=\"SERVFAIL\"}  # Errors indicate overload\ncoredns_dns_request_duration_seconds_bucket  # Latency\n```", "right-sizing", p),

        make_pair("expert-classification-018", "How do I classify workloads by their failure cost to determine right-sizing aggressiveness?", "## Failure Cost Classification\n\n**Right-sizing aggressiveness should be inversely proportional to failure cost.**\n\n| Failure Cost | Examples | Right-Sizing Approach |\n|-------------|---------|----------------------|\n| **Catastrophic** ($100K+/hr) | Payment processing, trading engine, auth service | Conservative: P99 + 40% headroom, Guaranteed QoS, no CPU limit removal, human review every change |\n| **High** ($10K-100K/hr) | Primary API, search service, checkout | Moderate: P95 + 25% headroom, burstable QoS OK, staged rollout over 48h |\n| **Medium** ($1K-10K/hr) | Internal APIs, background processing, analytics | Standard: P95 + 15% headroom, VPA recommendation + auto-apply in maintenance window |\n| **Low** ($100-1K/hr) | Dev environments, internal tools, batch jobs | Aggressive: P90 + 10% headroom, VPA Auto, accept occasional restarts |\n| **Negligible** (<$100/hr) | Personal dev, experiments, one-off jobs | Maximum: P50, minimal headroom, optimize for cost |\n\n**Calculating failure cost:**\n```\nfailure_cost = revenue_per_hour * impact_percentage\n             + engineer_cost * incident_duration\n             + reputation_cost (estimated)\n```\n\n**Label convention:**\n```yaml\nmetadata:\n  labels:\n    sage.io/failure-cost: \"high\"  # catastrophic/high/medium/low/negligible\n```\n\nk8s-sage uses this label to adjust headroom multipliers and recommendation confidence thresholds automatically.", "classification", p),
    ]


